{"title_page": "Glen Dexter", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian former sailor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox sailor\n| name           = Glen Dexter \n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =  \n| birth_name     =\n| fullname       =  Glen Vincent Dexter\n| nickname       =\n| nationality    = Canadian\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1952|11|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Lunenburg, Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         = {{convert|1.83|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| weight         =\n| classes        = [[Soling]]\n| club           =\n| collegeteam    =\n| coach          =\n| medaltemplates-title = Competition record\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry|{{CAN}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|World Championships}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[Soling World Championships|1977 Hanko]]|[[Soling]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[Soling World Championships|1978 Rio]]|[[Soling]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[Soling World Championships|1980 Ponce]]|[[Soling]]}}\n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n'''Glen Vincent Dexter''' (born 1 November 1952) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] former [[Sailing (sport)|sailor]] who competed in the [[1976 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=sref>{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/de/glen-dexter-1.html |accessdate=24 April 2013}}</ref> He was a member of the youngest Olympic sailing crew at the 1976 Olympics, with fellow sailors [[Andreas Josenhans]] and [[Sandy MacMillan]]. The team placed 8th. The team went on to become the World Class Soling Champions in 1977 and 1980.\n\n==Early life and education==\nDexter graduated from Dalhousie University with a Bachelor of Science with honours in Physics and then graduated with Bachelor of Laws in 1982. He also obtained a Master of Mathematics from [[University of Waterloo]].\n\n==Business career==\nDexter, along with former Olympic partners Andreas Josenhans and Sandy MacMillan, founded North Sails Atlantic, the largest sail manufacturing firm in Nova Scotia.<ref>[http://thechronicleherald.ca/olympics2012/127794-risks-rewards-in-sport-business Risks, rewards in sport, business] Chronicle Herald</ref> Dexter practised corporate law for 15 years with the law firm, Stewart McKelvey Stirling Scales. Dexter is President and CEO of Canadian International Capital and Chairman of Medusa Medical Technologies, a health care related software company.<ref>[http://www.cicnova.com/default.asp?mn=1.3.25 CIC Nova \u2013 Our Team]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Footer World Champions Soling}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dexter, Glen}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of Canada]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1976 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:World Champions Soling]]\n\n{{Canada-yachtracing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian former sailor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox sailor\n| name           = Glen Dexter \n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =  \n| birth_name     =\n| fullname       =  Glen Vincent Dexter\n| nickname       =\n| nationality    = Canadian\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1952|11|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Lunenburg, Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         = {{convert|1.83|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| weight         =\n| classes        = [[Soling]]\n| club           =\n| collegeteam    =\n| coach          =\n| medaltemplates-title = Competition record\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry|{{CAN}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|World Championships}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[Soling World Championships|1977 Hanko]]|[[Soling]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[Soling World Championships|1978 Rio]]|[[Soling]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[Soling World Championships|1980 Ponce]]|[[Soling]]}}\n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n'''Glen Vincent Dexter''' (born 1 November 1952) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] former [[Sailing (sport)|sailor]] who competed in the [[1976 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=sref>{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/de/glen-dexter-1.html |accessdate=24 April 2013}}</ref> He was a member of the youngest Olympic sailing crew at the 1976 Olympics, with fellow sailors [[Andreas Josenhans]] and [[Sandy MacMillan]]. The team placed 8th. The team went on to become the World Class Soling Champions in 1977 and 1980.\n\n==Early life and education==\nDexter graduated from Dalhousie University with a Bachelor of Science with honours in Physics and then graduated with Bachelor of Laws in 1982. He also obtained a Master of Mathematics from [[University of Waterloo]].\n\n==Business career==\nDexter, along with former Olympic partners Andreas Josenhans and Sandy MacMillan, founded North Sails Atlantic, the largest sail manufacturing firm in Nova Scotia.<ref>[http://thechronicleherald.ca/olympics2012/127794-risks-rewards-in-sport-business Risks, rewards in sport, business] Chronicle Herald</ref> Dexter practised corporate law for 15 years with the law firm, Stewart McKelvey Stirling Scales. Dexter is President and CEO of Canadian International Capital and Chairman of Medusa Medical Technologies, a health care related software company.<ref>[http://www.cicnova.com/default.asp?mn=1.3.25 CIC Nova \u2013 Our Team]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Footer World Champions Soling}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dexter, Glen}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of Canada]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1976 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:Soling class world champions]]\n\n{{Canada-yachtracing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dragon Genoa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glen_Dexter"}
{"title_page": "George Aguilar", "text_new": "\n\n{{short description|American actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = George Aguilar\n| image         = \n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = \n| birth_place = [[United States]]\n| spouse        = [[Josiane Balasko]] (2003\u2013present)\n| yearsactive = 1972\u2013present\n| othername     =\n| website      = \n|}}\n\n'''George Aguilar''' is an American actor.\n\n==Career==\nAguilar is probably best known for his work on ''[[Bagdad Cafe]]'' (1987), ''[[The Scarlet Letter (1995 film)|The Scarlet Letter]]'' (1995) and the miniseries ''[[Neverland (miniseries)|Neverland]]'' (2011).\n\n==Personal life==\n{{expand section|date= April 2015}}\nAguilar has been married to French actress [[Josiane Balasko]] since 2003. They reside in the [[Paris]] area.<ref name=Flint />\n\nA son, also named George Aguilar, was a car mechanic and aspiring actor who with his father appeared in ''The Scarlet Letter'' (1995) and ''Into The West'' (2005); he died in 2008 at age 28.<ref name=Flint>{{cite news| title= Flint Township actor George Aguilar remembered as loving family man | first= Marjory |last= Raymer | date= 19 October 2008| url= http://www.mlive.com/living/flint/index.ssf/2008/10/flint_township_actor_george_ag.html | accessdate= 9 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\" | Year\n! style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\" | Title\n! style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\" | Role\n! style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\" | Director\n! style=\"background: #CCCCCC;\" | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=1| 1972\n| ''[[Ulzana's Raid]]''\n| Indian Brave\n| [[Robert Aldrich]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=1| 1974\n| ''[[The Trial of Billy Jack]]''\n| Elk's Shadow\n| [[Tom Laughlin]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 1977\n| ''[[The Life and Times of Grizzly Adams]]''\n| \n| Jack B. Hively\n| TV Series (1 Episode)\n|-\n| ''[[A