views)<ref name=\"rotmanofsteel\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/superman_man_of_steel/|title=Man of Steel|publisher=[[Flixster]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=October 15, 2013}}</ref>\n| 55 (47 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/man-of-steel| title=Man of Steel|publisher=[[CBS]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=July 9, 2013}}</ref>\n| A\u2212<ref name=\"Scs\" />\n|-\n| ''Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice''\n|  28% (413 reviews)<ref name=rotdawn>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/batman_v_superman_dawn_of_justice/|title=Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice |publisher=[[Flixster]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref>\n| 44 (51 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/batman-v-superman-dawn-of-justice| title=Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice|publisher=[[CBS]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=March 30, 2016}}</ref>\n| B<ref name=\"Scs\" />\n|-\n|-\n| ''Justice League''\n|  40% (382 reviews)<ref name=\"rotJL\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/justice_league_2017|title=Justice League (2017)|work=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n|  45 (52 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/justice-league|title=Justice League Reviews|work=Metacritic|accessdate=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n|  B+<ref name=\"Scs\" />\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" | <small>'''List indicator(s)'''</small>\n* <small>A dark grey cell indicates the information is not available for the film.</small>\n|}\n\n==Home media==\n===Collections===\nThe initial four Superman films were released previously on [[VHS]], and throughout the film series' history, three [[box set]]s of the films have been released by Warner Bros. The first occurred on May 1, 2001, when ''The Complete Superman Collection'' was released both on DVD and [[VHS]], containing that year's DVD/home video releases of ''Superman'', ''Superman II'', ''Superman III'', and ''Superman IV''. The set was valued at US$49.99 for the DVD release and US$29.99 for the VHS release, and received positive reviews.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,108170,00.html|title=The Complete Superman Collection (2001)|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=2008-12-31|date=May 4, 2001}}</ref>\n\nThe four Christopher Reeve films were again released on November 28, 2006, in new DVD releases to coincide with ''[[Superman Returns]]'', also released in that year. ''Superman'' was released in a four-disc '[[special edition]]' similar to ''Superman II'', which was released in a two-disc special edition. Both ''Superman III'' and ''IV'' were released in single disc '[[deluxe edition]]s', and all four releases were available together in ''The Christopher Reeve Superman Collection'', an 8-disc set that was valued at US$79.92. Like the 2001 set before it, ''The Christopher Reeve Superman Collection'' received positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ugo.com/ugo/html/article/?id=16168 |title=The Christopher Reeve Superman Collection DVD Review|publisher=UGO.com |accessdate=2008-12-31|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214040526/http://www.ugo.com/ugo/html/article/?id=16168|archivedate=February 14, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAlso on November 28, 2006, a 14-disc DVD box set titled ''Superman Ultimate Collector's Edition'' was released, containing ''Superman'', ''Superman II'', ''[[Superman II: The Richard Donner Cut]]'', ''Superman III'', ''Superman IV'', ''Superman Returns'', and ''[[Look, Up in the Sky: The Amazing Story of Superman]]'', among other releases. All contents of the set were housed within a [[tin]] case. The set was valued at US$99.92, and received extremely positive reviews when first released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/25423/superman-ultimate-collectors-edition/|title=Superman Ultimate Collector's Edition|publisher=[[DVD Talk]]|accessdate=2008-12-31}}</ref> However, after only a day on the market, Warner Bros. announced that there were two errors discovered within the set. The first was that the 2.0 audio track on ''Superman'', was instead the 5.1 audio track already on the disc. The second was that the ''Superman III'' disc was not the 2006 deluxe edition as advertised, but the 2001 release instead. The set was soon recalled, and Warner Bros. offered a toll-free number to replace the faulty discs for people who had already purchased the set.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/NE1fU162IXA442|title=Warner Bros. Issues Statement Regarding Superman Ultimate Collector's Edition|publisher=Movie Web|accessdate=2008-12-31}}</ref> Due to popular demand, a corrected set was released and ''Superman Ultimate Collector's Edition'' returned to store shelves on May 29, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.superherohype.com/news/supermannews.php?id=5432|title=Superman Ultimate Collector's Edition Returns May 29|publisher=[[Superhero Hype!]]|accessdate=2008-12-31}}</ref>\n\nOn October 14, 2008, another Christopher Reeve Superman film collection was released, entitled ''Superman: 4 Film Favorites'', containing all four films, but with far less bonus material than previous sets. The collection was a 2-disc [[DVD-9|DVD-18]] set that included the first disc of both special editions from the 2006 release and both deluxe editions.\n\nOn April 1, 2011, it was announced that the entire Superman anthology would be making its way to [[Blu-ray]] for the first time. The anthology box set was released on June 7, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/49083/superman-the-motion-picture-anthology/|title=Superman: The Motion Picture Anthology (Blu-ray) |date= June 7, 2011|work=DVD Talk|accessdate=November 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[[Superman curse]]: a series of supposedly related incidents, sometimes fatal, that have affected many associated in producing Superman in film and animation\n* [[Superman franchise media]]\n* [[:Category:Fan films based on Superman]]\n* [[Batman in film]]\n{{Portal bar|Speculative fiction|Film|United States}}\n*[[Steel (film)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Superman in popular media}}\n{{DC Comics films}}\n{{Superman}}\n\n<!--Primary grouping categories-->\n\n[[Category:Superman films| ]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSteel (disambiguation)(link changed toSteel (1997 film)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Superman_in_film"}
{"title_page": "The Doon School", "text_new": "{{in use}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{short description|Boys' boarding school in Dehradun, India}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n | image                   = The Doon School.jpg\n | caption                 = Main Building at The Doon School\n | image_size              = 300px\n | name                    = The Doon School\n | logo                    = The Doon School, Dehradun - logo.png\n | logo_size               = 150px\n | colours                 = Blue & White {{color box|#005293}} {{color box|white}}\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|30.333|78.030|type:edu_region:IN|display=title}}\n | pushpin_map             = India Uttarakhand#India\n | location                = The Doon School<br>Mall Road<br>[[Dehradun]]&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;248001<br>India<br>([https://www.google.co.in/maps/place/The+Doon+School/@30.3350253,78.0298105,17z Google Map], [https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/158385701 OpenStreetMap])\n | specialist              = \n | schooltype              = Private [[boarding school]]\n | motto                   = '' Knowledge our Light''\n | sister_school           = [[Welham Girls' School]]\n | established             = \n | founded                 = {{Start date and age|1935|09|10}}\n | founder                 = [[Satish Ranjan Das]]\n | head_name               = Founder Headmaster\n | head                    = [[Arthur Foot|Arthur Edward Foot]]\n | gender                  = Boys\n | lower_age               = 12\n | upper_age               = 18\n | headmaster              = Post vacant \n | chair_label             = Chairman of Governors\n | chair                   = [[Sunil Kant Munjal]]\n | pupils                  = c. 600\n | faculty                 = 70\n | houses                  = 5 houses + 2 holding houses\n | campus                  = 72 acres (297,314&nbsp;m\u00b2)\n | ceeb                    = 671616\n | district                = [[Dehradun district|Dehradun District]]\n | student_union           = [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n | affiliation             = [[International Baccalaureate|IB]]<br>[[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examination|CISCE]]<br>[[International General Certificate of Secondary Education|IGCSE]]\n | publication             = ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]''\n | free_label2             = Annual fees\n | free_text2              = {{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1025000}} (home students)<br>{{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1281000}} (international)\n | free_label              = Former pupils\n | free_text               = [[List of The Doon School alumni|Doscos]]\n | website                 = [http://www.doonschool.com/ www.doonschool.com]\n}}\n\n'''The Doon School''' (informally '''Doon School''' or '''Doon''') is a boys-only private [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]], [[Selective school|selective]] boarding school in Dehradun, Uttarakhand, India, established in 1935. It was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a [[Kolkata]] lawyer, who prevised a school modelled on the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[public school (United Kingdom)|public school]], but conscious of Indian ambitions and desires. Although he died in 1928, he is considered the founder of the school. The school's first [[Head teacher|headmaster]] was [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], an Englishman who had spent nine years as a science master at [[Eton College]], England.<ref>{{cite book|year=1979|chapter=FOOT, Arthur Edward|title=Who Was Who 1961\u20131970|location=London|publisher=A. & C. Black|isbn=0-7136-2008-0}}</ref> The last headmaster was [[Matthew Raggett]], who resigned in January 2020. He was the fourth British headmaster in Doon's history and a member of [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]], [[UK]].\n\nThe school houses roughly 500 pupils aged 12 to 18, and admission is based on a competitive entrance examination, a group discussion and an interview with the headmaster. Every year in January and April, the school admits pupils aged 13 in Grade 7 (known as D-form) and aged 14 in Grade 8 (C-form) respectively. Boys take the [[IGCSE]] exam in Grade 10, and for the final two years can choose between [[Indian School Certificate]] or [[International Baccalaureate]] curriculum. Doon remains a boys-only school despite continued pressure from political leaders, including former [[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]], to become [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]]. [[Old boy network|Old boys]] of the school are known as 'Doscos'. \n\nDoon has been consistently ranked the best all-boys residential school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/17-schools-from-u---khand-secure-top-10-positions-in-ewisr.html|title=17 schools from U\u2019khand secure Top 10 positions in EWISR|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> Although the school has often been cited as 'Eton of India' by media outlets such as the [[BBC]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02c3zgq|title=BBC World Service - Witness, India's Eton|website=BBC}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|author=STEVEN R. WEISMAN, Special to the New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/12/world/india-s-old-school-tie-harrow-by-the-himalayas.html |title=India'S Old School Tie - Harrow By The Himalayas |location=Dehra Dun (India); India |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=12 November 1985 |accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/aug/13/fiction.arundhatiroy|title=The lost sub-continent|first=William|last=Dalrymple|date=13 August 2005|website=the Guardian}}</ref> ''[[The Spectator]]'',<ref name=\"Spectator UK\">{{cite web|author=Read |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/03/its-a-spartan-life-at-the-eton-of-india/# |title=It's a spartan life at 'the Eton of India' |publisher=The Spectator |date= |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/alastair-sooke/7546719/The-rise-and-rise-of-Anish-Kapoor-Inc..html|title=The rise & rise of Anish Kapoor Inc.|first=Alastair|last=Sooke|date=2 April 2010|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> and ''[[Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Remnick |first=David |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1987/10/20/rajiv-gandhi-and-the-mantle-unsought/779cee82-b666-4248-8116-278d6134a002/ |title=Rajiv Gandhi And The Mantle Unsought |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1987-10-20 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> it strongly eschews the label.<ref name=\"Spectator UK\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/deep-focus/Doon-of-India-wants-to-conquer-the-globe/articleshow/6800690.cms |title=\u2018Doon of India\u2019 wants to conquer the globe - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2010-10-24 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has educated a wide range of notable alumni, including politicians, diplomats, artists, writers and business leaders.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709213757/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 July 2012 |title=For wannabe Doons, don from hills is a boon |newspaper=Times of India |date=30 December 2002 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> Among the former pupils of Doon are the late Indian prime minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]], artist [[Anish Kapoor]], novelists [[Vikram Seth]] and [[Amitav Ghosh]], fashion designer [[Tarun Tahiliani]], mountaineer [[Nandu Jayal]] and social activist [[Bunker Roy]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\n[[File:The Doon School main building (then FRI) - 1917.jpg|thumb|250px|Main building of Doon in 1917, when it was part of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]].]]\n[[File:Main Gate, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main gate of the Doon School.]]\nDoon was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a lawyer from Calcutta and advocate-general of Bengal, who in 1927 became a member of the [[Viceroy's Executive Council]] of [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Irwin]] on the condition that he would use the prestige of this position to raise funds for a new type of school in [[India]].<ref name=\"auto\">MacDougall2006, p.100</ref> He decided to name the new school \"Doon\", as it was situated in the [[Doon Valley]]. He travelled widely in [[India]] with the goal of collecting {{Indian Rupee}}4&nbsp;million, but at the time of his death had raised only {{Indian Rupee}}1 million in cash and a further {{Indian Rupee}}1&nbsp;million in promises.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |pages=360 |jstor=41364317}}</ref>  With the money, Das formed the Indian Public Schools' Society (IPSS), which had the objective of founding new public schools in [[India]] that would admit students regardless of caste, creed or social status. Under the IPSS, a Board of Governors supervises all matters of Doon.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 41: \"...the body founded by Das for the purposes of establishing the Doon School, the Indian Public Schools Society\"</ref>\n\nAfter the death of Das in 1928, the IPSS accomplished little, and by 1934 some of the original lenders had begun to inquire about the return of their money.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |pages=360 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> To solve this problem, Sir Joseph Bhore, then Railway Minister of [[Freeman Freeman-Thomas, 1st Marquess of Willingdon|Lord Willingdon's]] Council, became IPSS chairman and, with [[Akbar Hydari|Sir Akbar Hydari]] as secretary, worked to obtain the former estate of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] in [[Dehra Dun]] on favourable terms.<ref>''The Indian Year Book'', vol. 29 (1942), p. 419: \"Doon School&nbsp;\u2013 This school which is established in the Chand Bagh and Skinner's Estates at Dehra Doon owes its origin to the initiative and enthusiasm of the late SR Das.\"</ref> Sir Frank Noyce also joined the team. [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Halifax]], then President of the British Board of Education, led a selection committee that nominated [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], a science teacher at [[Eton College]], to be the first headmaster. On 27 October 1935, the [[Viceroy]], [[Lord Willingdon]], presided over the formal opening of the school. Seventy boys enrolled in the first [[Academic term|term]], and 110 more signed up for the second.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 203 (Note 12): \"...from Willingdon's inaugural address on 27 October 1935\"</ref> \n\n===Early years:1935\u20131970===\n\nFoot had never visited [[India]] before accepting the position of headmaster. He noted that the school appeared to be surrounded by forests and close to mountains, and the possibilities of outdoor recreation and mountaineering seem to have influenced his decision as much as the chance to create a completely new type of school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |pages=359 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> Foot's first action upon being offered the position was to recruit [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J.A.K. (John) Martyn]] from [[Harrow School]] as his deputy. Doon's ethos and guiding principles were determined early in its life by Foot, Martyn, [[R. L. Holdsworth|R.L. Holdsworth]] and [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]], who went on to become principal of [[Mayo College]].<ref>{{cite web|author=site admin |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/books/story/19851115-book-review-sumer-singh-doon-the-story-of-a-school-mady-martyn-martyn-sahib-802174-2014-01-16 |title=Where East meets West - Society & The Arts News - Issue Date: Nov 15, 1985 |publisher=Indiatoday.in |date=1985-11-15 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> They were soon joined in their efforts by Indians such as the artist [[Sudhir Khastgir]] (the school's first art teacher, who had trained previously in [[Santiniketan]]) and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], a noted mountaineer who taught at Doon for several decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> In an essay entitled ''The Objects of Education'' published in the school magazine, Foot offered a template for a complete education for boys, which included teaching them to form a habit of choosing good over evil, think logically, express their thoughts and views clearly, and maintain a healthy body.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\" /> \n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  =...&nbsp;By 14 he should have learnt all the ordinary principles of social behaviour. He should know how to stand up and speak to a variety of different types of people&nbsp;\u2013 to his own mother, to someone else's mother, to his father, to his schoolmasters, to servants, to Mahatma Gandhi or to the Viceroy, and to do this without any self-consciousness&nbsp;...At 17 must come another quality, less instinctive and requiring a maturer mind: he must acquire a capacity of judgement.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\">{{cite book|title=The Doon School Sixty Years On |publisher=Doon School Old Boys' Society|date=October 1996}}</ref>&nbsp;...\n |source = <small>Arthur Foot, 1946, ''The Objects of Education''</small>\n |align  = left\n |width  = 30%\n}}\n\nThe annual school fees in 1935 was {{Indian Rupee}}1,375, and by September 1946, it had risen to {{Indian Rupee}}1,800.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |pages=360 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> In 1947, there were around 300 boys studying at Doon, out of which 50-60 were [[Muslims]], 15-20 [[Sikhs]], 15-20 [[Parsees]], 6-7 Christians, and the remaining two-thirds Hindu.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |pages=365 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> Martyn, who became the second headmaster in 1948, acknowledged the influence of German educator [[Kurt Hahn]] in the development of the school's ethos. Although Martyn had not visited India before, he immediately accepted Foot's offer because of the opportunity it afforded to implement Hahn's ideas, which he had not been able to do at Harrow.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=38|quote=When John wrote to Hahn to tell him we was going to India, Hahn replied that he had been waiting to be able to offer him a place at Gordonstoun...}}</ref> While Foot and Martyn were determined to model Doon on Eton and Harrow, they both agreed that Doon should cater primarily for Indian boys\u2014and not the sons of British expatriates\u2014in order to create a uniquely Indian public school rather than a transplanted British institution. Foot did not want Doon to be considered elitist. At the opening of the school, he said, \"Our boys will join an aristocracy, but it\u2019s an aristocracy of service inspired by ideals of unselfishness, not one of wealth, privilege or position\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/academy/interview_doon-school-is-popular-for-building-an-aristocracy-of-service_1392063 |title=Doon School is popular for building an 'aristocracy of service'&nbsp;\u2013 Academy|work=DNA |date=5 June 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> In a paper surveying the new school, presented to the [[Royal Society of Arts]], London in 1947, Foot wrote: \"In language we have never intended to base our instruction on the Classics in the way that Latin is still the centre pin of the English Public School. The great majority of boys take Urdu or Hindi.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |pages=361 |jstor=41364317}}</ref>\n\n===Middle years: 1970\u20132000===\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; clear:left; margin-right:1em; font-size:85%; background:#ffc; color:black; width:20em; max-width:25%;\" cellspacing=\"5\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Headmasters\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n* [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], 1935\u20131948\n* [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J. A. K. Martyn]], 1948\u20131966\n* [[C. J. Miller]], 1966\u20131970\n* [[Eric Simeon|Eric J. Simeon]], 1970\u20131979\n* [[Gulab Ramchandani]], 1979\u20131988\n* [[Shomie Das]], 1988\u20131996\n* [[John Mason (Schoolmaster)|John A. Mason]], 1996\u20132003\n* [[Kanti Bajpai]], 2003\u20132009\n* [[Peter McLaughlin]], 2009\u20132016\n* [[Matthew Raggett]], 2016\u20132020 \n|}\n\nThe school's first Indian headmaster was [[Eric Simeon]], appointed in 1970. He came from a military background and laid great emphasis on disciplined living.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/schooled-for-life/32471/|title=Schooled for life - Indian Express|website=archive.indianexpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/05/16/stories/2007051615082000.htm |title=Lt. Col. Eric Joseph Simeon dead |work=The Hindu |date=16 May 2007 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> Simeon's tenure of nine years was marked with financial difficulties for the school and the estate suffered, as the funds were not enough to maintain buildings and facilities. <ref>https://www.doonschool.com/weekly/May%2019%202007.pdf</ref> In 1971, Simeon introduced the 'Scholar's Blazer', an academic equivalent of the pre-existing prize 'Games Blazer', so that boys accorded academic excellence the same level of prestige as they did sporting achievements.<ref name=\"Back to School\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/KaranThapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104092100/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/karanthapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 November 2010 |last=Thapar|first=Karan|title=Back to School |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1979, [[Gulab Ramchandani]] became the first alumnus to be appointed headmaster, and during his term the school regained financial stability.<ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/ramchandani-old-boy-and-workaholic-headmaster-who-transformed-doon-school/articleshow/58185206.cms</ref> In 1988, [[Shomie Das]], another alumnus and the grandson of school founder Satish Ranjan Das, became headmaster. Das's focus was on upgrading the school infrastructure, and the Oberoi house was added to the original four houses. The next headmaster, [[John Mason (schoolmaster)|John Mason]], appointed in 1996, planned on making Doon more affordable to school pupils. The school did not raise its fees while Mason was in office. \n\n====Criticism of Rajiv Gandhi administration====\n\nIn the 1980s, the then [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Rajiv Gandhi]], an alumnus, drew criticism from the media for appointing many old boys to his administration. His inner circle was labelled a \"Doon cabinet\" or \"Dosco Mafia\"<ref>''Indian Tales of the Raj'' by Zareer Masani, p.152</ref> and ''Washington Post'' reported, \"The catch phrase around Delhi these days is that the 'Doon School runs India,' but that is too simple an analysis for a complex, chaotic country with so many competing spheres of influence.\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\">{{cite web|last=Bumiller |first=Elisabeth |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1985/11/24/where-indias-elite-were-boys-together/0579f3d9-1835-4441-b1b1-a55e3111bdc3/ |title=Where India's Elite Were Boys Together |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1985-11-24 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Steven R. Weisman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/20/magazine/the-rajiv-generation.html |title=THE RAJIV GENERATION - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1986-04-20 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Gandhi's reliance on Doon alumni for political advice later led Prime Minister [[Morarji Desai]] to remark, \"If I had anything to do with this place, I'd close it down\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1987/0724/eindia.html|title=Bootstrap steps for Gandhi|date=24 July 1987|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref> Although any alumnus seldom held public office for some time afterward, this changed with the political ascendance of Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia, Naveen Patnaik, and Rahul Gandhi.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707070626/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 July 2012 |title=Naveen Patnaik sets stage for GeNext Doscos |newspaper=The Times of India |date=10 May 2004 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Recent years: 2000\u2013present===\n[[Kanti Bajpai]] was the third old boy, after Gulab Ramchandani and Shomie Das, to become headmaste, when appointed to the post in 2003. He introduced numerous punishments, notably \"yellow cards\", to control an outburst of bullying at Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03cgg70 |title=BBC World Service - Path to Power, Educating India's Elite |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1994-10-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> In 2006, Bajpai found himself embroiled in a controversy when the parents of Hindu and Sikh students complained on discovering that the school's dining hall only serves [[halal]] meat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bad-blood-over-meat-served-at-Doon-School/articleshow/1516879.cms|title=Bad blood over meat served at Doon School &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The fact came to light after a visiting Pakistani delegation was assured of their meal's halal status. Despite mounting pressure, the school's board of governors appealed for maintaining the status quo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/doon-debates-meaty-matters/story-mQ4y1Lt1fXLI3DiW2cV3XI.html|title=Doon debates meaty matters|date=3 May 2006|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> As of 2016, the school was serving both halal and non-halal (''[[jhatka]]'') meat varieties in the dining hall.<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2434-FINAL.pdf</ref> In 2009, [[Peter McLaughlin]], an Irish academic, was chosen to lead the school, becoming the first non-Indian headmaster in almost four decades.\n\n====2010 Founder's Day celebrations and film controversy====\n[[File:President of India speaking at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]] speaking at the school's 75th Founder's Day in October 2010.]]\n\nFounder's Day is a three-four day event in the autumn term, usually October, that marks the school's founding and draws many ex-pupils from all parts of the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/columnists/item/40943-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref> The chief guest is usually a prominent person.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/education/how-indias-renowned-doon-school-is-embracing-change-to-retain-its-exclusivity/articleshow/45006985.cms?from=mdr |title=How India's renowned Doon School is embracing change to retain its exclusivity - The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=2014-11-02 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The events include exhibitions, productions of plays, yoga sessions, live bands, a fete and an orchestral concert given by members of the school's Music Society.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Hill Post|url=http://hillpost.in/2011/10/28/doon-school-celebrates-76-th-founders-day/33352/latest-news/bhatt |title=Doon School celebrates 76 th founders day |date=28 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Datta |first=Sravasti |url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523113538/http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 May 2011 |title=Life & Style / Metroplus : All boarders on board |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=28 February 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon celebrated its 75th Founder's Day in 2010 and programmed events on an unprecedented scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/doon-school-to-celebrate-its-75th-anniversary-from-oct-21/articleshow/6712783.cms?from=mdr|title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21|date=8 October 2010|via=The Economic Times}}</ref><ref name=\"hindustantimes.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/boys-will-be-boys/story-UxdKhDLhEGUVHIwaXe2e7H.html|title=Boys will be boys |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The event was christened ''DS-75''.<ref name=\"Doon school\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-08/news/27591639_1_celebrations-doon-school-chief-guest |title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21 |publisher=[[The Times Group]] |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School\">{{cite news|title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/15930-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |newspaper=Daily Pioneer|date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Among the chief guests were the then President [[Pratibha Patil]] of India, King [[Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck]] of Bhutan and [[Kapil Sibal]], (then [[Ministry of Human Resource Development (India)|Union Minister for Human Resource Development]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bhutanjournals.com/monarchy/hms-address-at-doon-school-dehradun-india/ |title=HM's Address at Doon School, Dehradun, India|newspaper=Bhutan Journals |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Pratibha Patil, in her address, urged the school authorities to make Doon a co-educational institution.<ref name=\"telegraphindia1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1101025/jsp/frontpage/story_13097199.jsp |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|title=Dame dilemma for Doon&nbsp;\u2013 President's co-ed suggestion evokes mixed reaction |date=25 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> One of the main events was a discussion, dubbed the \"Chandbagh Debate\", held between alumni including [[Vikram Seth]], [[Kamal Nath]], [[Manpreet Singh Badal]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]] and retired headmaster Kanti Bajpai, on the topic ''Can India lead?''. It was moderated by television commentator [[Karan Thapar]], an alumnus of the school.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/A+matter+of+debate+at+Doon+School+platinum+jubilee.-a0240443417 |title=A matter of debate at Doon School platinum jubilee|newspaper=[[India Today]] |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Ashvin Kumar]], an alumnus and Oscar-nominated director, made the film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'' for the celebrations, using pupils for the cast and crew. Most of it was shot in June and July during the summer break, and those scenes which required the entire student body were filmed after the school reopened in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imaginox.co.uk/course/1718 |title=Making 'Dazed in Doon' |publisher=Imaginox |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> It was screened on the final day of celebrations to a gathering of over 2000 people, including guests, students, parents and alumni.<ref name=dazed>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-14/news-interviews/28271042_1_film-doon-school-ashvin-kumar|title=Doon School bans Ashvin Kumar's film|newspaper=The Times of India|date=14 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> The day after screening, the school objected to the film and its distribution, obtaining a court order to delay its release and labelling it \"defamatory\".<ref name=fallout>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-18/news-interviews/28230561_1_doon-short-film-ashvin|title=Doon film fallout!|newspaper=The Times of India|date=18 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> The DVD sales on campus were immediately halted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Doon-School-bans-Ashvin-Kumars-film/articleshow/6919672.cms|title=Doon School bans Ashvin Kumar's film - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref name=ex-student-film>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-25/india/28269703_1_doon-school-ashvin-kumar-cbfc|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120701125916/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-25/india/28269703_1_doon-school-ashvin-kumar-cbfc|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 July 2012|title=Ex-student's film celebrating Doon draws school's ire|newspaper=The Times of India|date=25 December 2010}}</ref> The dispute  remains unresolved between the director and school authorities. On 22 October 2010, a commemorative postage stamp depicting the school's main building was released by the [[Indian Postal Service]] to mark the occasion of the 75th Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101009/dplus.htm#5 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=The Tribune |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Present day====\nIn June 2016, the school announced the appointment of Matthew Raggett, principal of the [[Leipzig International School]]'s secondary department, to succeed Peter McLaughlin as headmaster. Until the start of McLaughlin's headmastership, the student demographic was dominated by boys hailing from the [[North Indian]] states. To make the school more diverse, Raggett continued McLaughlin's outreach initiative of inviting more applications from boys in [[South Indian|South]] and [[Northeast India|Northeast Indian]] states.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/doon-school-looks-for-more-boys-from-south/articleshow/57725021.cms|title=Doon School: Doon School looks for more boys from south &#124; Bengaluru News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/doons-bonds-with-hyderabad/article7072329.ece|title=Doon\u2019s bonds with Hyderabad|first=R. Ravikanth|last=Reddy|date=6 April 2015|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> He also introduced a group discussion as part of the admissions process to test for critical thinking and peer interaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/dehradun/after-8-decades-doon-school-looks-to-south-east-for-students/story-4uYQRMF8qalW61HFHuB0xM.html|title=After 8 decades, Doon School looks to South, East for students|date=3 July 2017|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> In January 2020, Matthew Raggett stepped down as the tenth headmaster citing personal reasons. In March 2020, the school was shut down and boys were sent home due to the [[COVID-19 outbreak]] and the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|Indian lockdown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/three-city-based-boarding-schools-close/articleshow/74662334.cms|title=Coronavirus scare: Three city-based boarding schools close &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Online classes are being conducted for students through video conferencing apps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-launch-online-classes-to-complete-syllabus/articleshow/74781758.cms|title=Schools launch online classes to complete syllabus in parts of Uttarakhand &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:FC Barcelona camp at Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|Main Field of the school with Kashmir and Hyderabad houses in the background.]]\n\nThe school is spread across a single campus covering approximately {{convert|72|acre|m2}} flanked by Chakrata Road and Mall Road in the [[Dehradun Cantonment]] area of Dehradun city, [[Uttarakhand]], India.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB114929995090170584 |title=The Andover of India? |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |first=Anita|last=Raghavan|date=24 June 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To house the school, the IPSS acquired Chandbagh Estate in Dehradun from the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] (FRI). Part of the estate was once a deer park. The IPSS also acquired an adjoining estate, now known as Skinner's Field, from the descendants of [[James Skinner (East India Company officer)|James Skinner]]. \n\n===Architecture===\nThe construction of the Main Building, then in FRI, was carried out by Imperial Public Works Department, and finished in 1911. Its Renaissance-style architecture was inspired by [[Basilica Palladiana]] in [[Vicenza]], Italy.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\" /> Many buildings on the campus have been designed by notable Indian architects or firms.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\" /> The library was designed by Romi Khosla, the Biology block by Ram Sharma, teachers' residences by Anagram Architects, and the new Arts and Media Centre, which was inaugurated in October 2010 and shortlisted for the 2010 World Architecture News Education Award, by alumnus Sandeep Khosla <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/5-schools-india-teach-lesson-design-architecture-pune-mumbai/|title=5 schools in India that offer a quick course in sensitive design and architecture|date=10 January 2020|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sandeep Khosla, Principal Architect , Khosla Associates |url=https://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/article/1507033/making-cut |title=Making the cut |publisher=Worldarchitecturenews.com |date=2011-02-13 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Arts and Media Centre houses painting, ceramic, sculpture, and textile studios, along with a lecture hall, film and photography studio, publications' room and exhibition galleries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/86476/arts-and-media-centre-at-the-doon-school-khosla-associates/|title=Arts and Media Centre at the Doon School / Khosla Associates|date=4 November 2010|website=ArchDaily}}</ref> In 2016, the school's Main Building received an \"Honourable Mention\" under the [[UNESCO Asia Pacific Heritage Awards|UNESCO Asia-Pacific Awards for Cultural Heritage Conservation]], following the conservation work carried out by Aishwarya Tipnis Architects on the more than a century-old building.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/doon-school-campus-extension-anagram-architects/|title=Take a tour of India\u2019s most elite private school, The Doon School campus|date=21 March 2018|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.one.un.org/page/restoration-of-prayer-hall-at-japan-shrine-wins-top-honor-in-unesco-asia-pacific-heritage-awards/ |title=Restoration of prayer hall at Japan shrine wins top honor in UNESCO Asia- Pacific Heritage Awards - UN India |publisher=In.one.un.org |date=2016-09-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Natural environment===\nThe school estate, known as Chandbagh, lies in the green zone of the city and occupies the former site of the Imperial Forest Research Institute, now [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]]. A wide variety of [[flora]] and [[fauna]] are found on campus, including many rare trees that date back to the days of the FRI.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\">{{cite web|url=https://fountainink.in/essay/no-common-or-garden-affair |title=No common or garden affair &#124; Fountain Ink |publisher=Fountainink.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj\" /> The school has over 150 species of trees on its campus, and the formal gardens attract a variety of birds.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Prashant |first=Shishir |url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/doon-schools-etp-may-be-trendsetter/428364/ |title=Doon school's ETP may be trendsetter |newspaper=[[Business Standard]] |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1996, a book titled ''Trees of Chandbagh'' was released which provided a comprehensive account of vegetation found on Doon's campus.<ref name=\"TreesofChandbagh\">{{cite book|last=Sahni|first=K. C.|title=Trees of Chandbagh: Doon's national heritage|year=1996|publisher=Konark Publishers|location=Delhi|isbn=978-81-220-0457-1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> Along similar lines, the illustrated book ''Birds of Chandbagh: A Guide To Birding at The Doon School'' was released in 2019, featuring photographs, illustrations and [[QR codes]] documenting the [[bird calls]] of the species found on campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.in/BIRDS-CHANDBAGH-guide-birding-School/dp/B084HG4R87 |title=Buy BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Book Online at Low Prices in India &#124; BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Reviews & Ratings |publisher=Amazon.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has devised an Architectural and Projects Committee, which ensures that any construction taking place on campus is done without disturbing the ecological balance of the wooded school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/7-days/studies-in-style/cid/598008 |title=Studies in style |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2017-10-30 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Houses===\n[[File:TataHouseQuadinDoon.jpg|thumb|right|East wing of Tata House and the quad.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:80%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | House name and Colours\n|-\n! House\n! Colour\n! Swatch\n|-\n|Kashmir || Yellow || {{colour box|#fecb00}}\n|-\n|Oberoi || Sky blue || {{colour box|#00add0}}\n|-\n|Tata || Red || {{colour box|#c60c30}}\n|-\n|Jaipur || Green || {{colour box|#007934}}\n|-\n|Hyderabad || Navy Blue || {{colour box|#003359}}\n|-\n|Martyn || || {{colour box|#496c60}}\n|-\n|Foot || ||{{colour box|#589199}}\n|}\n\nDoon follows the [[house system]]; there are five main houses (Hyderabad, Jaipur, Kashmir, Tata and Oberoi) and two 'holding houses' (Foot and Martyn, named after former headmasters), for boys in their first year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/pastoral-care/boarding-at-doon/|title=Boarding at Doon|website=Doon School}}</ref> The original four houses (Oberoi was added in 1991) were named after the largest initial donors: Hyderabad House was named after [[Akbar Hydari]], who secured a contribution from [[Nizam of Hyderabad]]'s government; Kashmir House, after [[Maharajah]] [[Hari Singh]], then ruler of [[Jammu and Kashmir]]; Tata House, after the [[Tata family|Tata]] Trusts; and Jaipur House, after [[Rai Bahadur]] Amarnath Atal arranged for contributions from the [[Durbar (court)|Durbar]] of [[Jaipur]].<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 197 (Appendix 1): \"Donors to the Indian Public Schools' Society prior to 1936\"</ref> \n\nBoys are assigned to houses at the time of admission and develop great loyalty to them, since all [[intramural sports]] involve fierce competition between houses. Each house is run by a housemaster or a housemistress, along with a house captain and a team of [[School prefect|prefects]]. One senior boy serves as [[school captain]], chosen by teachers and students voting in a [[secret ballot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ludhiana/Ludhiana-lad-is-Doon-School-captain/articleshow/18424444.cms |title=Ludhiana lad is Doon School captain &#124; Ludhiana News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2013-02-10 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>  The housemistress is assisted by a [[matron]] known as \"The Dame\", who provides [[pastoral care]] for pupils, some of whom take several weeks to adjust fully to life in a boarding school, particularly given Doon's monastic lifestyle and strict routine.<ref name=\"outlookindia2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230938 |title=Class Up At Doon &#124; Anjali Puri |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Futehally\"> {{cite book |last1=Futehally |first1=Laeeq |title=The Last Englishman: The Life and Times of Jack Gibson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3iw1CgAAQBAJ&dq=the+last+englishman+jack+gibson&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2015 |publisher=Hachette UK |location=London |language= |isbn=9789350099698 |page= |chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= The food and linen was the responsibility of the Dame (Matron)}}</ref> The homes of housemasters and housemistresses are adjacent or physically attached to their houses to enable close supervision and support.\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main Building of the school which houses classrooms and offices.]]\nThe school practices a five-and-a-half-day week consisting of 40 periods (or \"schools\"), each of 40 minutes. The school day begins with \"first bell\" soon after 6:15&nbsp;am. The boys have [[chhota haazri]] before doing [[calisthenics]] outdoors on the playing fields, which is then followed by classes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2004-07-04/special-report/27149351_1_education-system-elite-schools-vikram-seth |title=Chhota Hazri bell tolls for desi Etons|newspaper=The Times of India |date=4 July 2004 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The student-teacher ratio at the school is 10:1.<ref name=\"excellence\">{{cite journal|title=Excellence personified |journal=Frontline |date=12 February 2011 |volume=28 |issue=4 |url=http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110313163529/http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 March 2011 |accessdate=2 March 2012 }}</ref> Doon pupils take the [[International General Certificate of Secondary Education]] (IGCSE) exams in [[tenth grade]], which replaced [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education]] in 2017, and are thereafter offered two strands for the final two years: [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB) or [[Indian School Certificate]] (ISC).<ref name=\"autogenerated2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ibo.org/en/school/002603 |title=The Doon School - International Baccalaureate\u00ae |publisher=Ibo.org |date=2006-08-28 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe academic year has three terms: spring, summer and autumn. New pupils (\"D-Formers or 7th Graders\") join Doon at the beginning of April.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kapoor |first=Jaskiran |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/class-apart/601507/0 |title=Class Apart |publisher=Indian Express |date=11 April 2010 |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref> The autumn term runs from August to the year-end examinations in November after which the boys are promoted to the new class beginning in February. These internal examinations are known as \"trials\", while examinations leading to certificates such as the [[Indian School Certificate]] are known as \"finals\". Discipline at the school has always been strict, and the school has expelled children from well-known families. In the 1950s, Martyn's suggestion that [[Sanjay Gandhi]] finish his senior year elsewhere was accepted without question by his mother, Indira Gandhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2008/20081202/dplus1.htm |title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India&nbsp;\u2014 Dehradun Plus |work=The Tribune |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> \n\nSocial work, known formally as \"Socially Useful Productive Work\", is also part of school life. All boys of the school must complete a mandatory quota of social service hours every term.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/141122/nation-education/article/doon-school-scouts-tamil-nadu-students |title=Doon School scouts for Tamil Nadu students |publisher=Deccanchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Doon also oversees a Panchayat Ghar teaching impoverished children, and many building projects and workshops for the local community. Pupils and alumni have frequently helped local villages of organised efforts across India to assist people affected by natural disasters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roundsquare.org/educational-insights/the-doon-school-a-village-service-partnership/ |title=The Doon School: A Village Service Partnership |publisher=Round Square |date=2019-02-19 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> During the [[1991 Uttarkashi earthquake]] the school's amateur radio club was used by the government for communication purposes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gautam|first=Ashutosh|title=Earthquake: A Natural Disaster|year=2008|publisher=APH Publishing|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-313-0337-5|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oSbTJDwMFgAC&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=doon+school+uttarkashi+earthquake#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20uttarkashi%20earthquake&f=false}}</ref>  \n\n===Traditions===\nThe early headmasters and teachers at Doon came from traditional British public schools, and the jargon introduced by them is still in use. For example, the weekly masters' meeting, started by Foot, is called ''Chambers'', a term taken from Eton, and evening \"prep\" (the boarding-school equivalent of homework) is called ''toye-time'', a term taken from [[Winchester College]].<ref>{{cite book|first1=Charles |last1=Stevens|first2=Christopher|last2=Stray|title=Winchester notions: the English dialect of Winchester College|publisher=Athlone Press|year=1998|page=294|quote=Toy-time, or toytime recorded from 1831 as the evening hours of preparation, called 'prep' elsewhere&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB917469665815143000 |title=Language Lessons: For India's Elite English Is the Past -- and the Future\n|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date= |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The school songs were deliberately chosen to include both [[Urdu poetry]] and Hindu [[bhajan]]s as a way of emphasising Doon's secular ethos; similarly, the school prayers include a mix of Anglican hymns and Indian poetry.<ref>The Doon School Prayer book p.02-26</ref> Attendance at the morning assembly is required of all pupils and teachers. It traditionally begins with a song from the school's Song Book, which includes: ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]], ''Chisti Ne Jis Zamin Mein'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''Anand Loke'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]]; ''[[Saare Jahan Se Achcha]]'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''[[Lab Pe Aati Hai Dua]]'' by Muhammad Iqbal; ''Vandana Ke in Swaron Mein'' (a [[Bhajan|bhajan]]); ''Ghungat Ke Pat Khol Re'' (attributed to [[Meerabai]]); ''Pitu Matu Sahayak'' (a bhajan); ''[[Vande Mataram]]'' (from a poem by [[Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay]]). Although ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' is India's [[National anthem]], it is traditionally referred to as \"Song No. 1\" at Doon since it was adopted as the School Song in 1935, fifteen years before it was adopted as India's national anthem.<ref>Bathla, Sanjeev<''Chotta Hazri:A Dosco's yatra'' p.32</ref><ref name=\"srivastava\">{{cite book|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School (p.82)|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WAdkjptj7zwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School&cd=2#v=onepage&q=song&f=false|isbn=9780415178563|year=1998}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\n{{Anchor|Athletics}}\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Cricket at Doon.jpg|thumb|left|A cricket game in progress on the Main Field.]]\n\nSports are compulsory for pupils. The school has over {{convert|30|acre|m2}} of playing fields, the largest of which are Skinner's Field and the Main Field. Cricket and hockey dominate the sports calendar in spring term, while football, athletics and boxing are played in autumn term. Other sports such as tennis, table tennis, badminton, squash, basketball, swimming and gymnastics are played all-year round. Inter-house matches are played in cricket, hockey, football and basketball. Sports facilities include a 25-metre swimming pool, a boxing ring and a multi-purpose hall with a gymnasium, yoga studio, and facilities for indoor badminton, basketball and table tennis. There are two [[artificial turf]] cricket pitches, five basketball courts, four tennis courts, four squash courts, eight cricket nets, seven fields for hockey and football (which can be converted to four cricket pitches to accommodate seasonal sports), a modern cricket pavilion and two 400-metre athletics tracks. In 2014, the school inaugurated a shooting range on campus. Golf is offered to boys in partnership with local golf courses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/academic-life/departments/sports/|title=Sports|website=Doon School}}</ref> Doon hosts the annual Afzal Khan Memorial Basketball Tournament, an inter-school tournament that draws all major school basketball teams of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/features/the-asian-school-bag-bball-trophy-233461 |title=The Asian School bag b\u2019ball trophy |publisher=The Tribune India |date=2016-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/inside-the-hoop-dreams-of-21-boys-at-nbas-first-academy-in-india/articleshow/58979953.cms?from=mdr |title=NBA: Inside the hoop dreams of 21 boys at NBA\u2019s first academy in India - The Economic Times |date=2017-06-04 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020504/ncr3.htm |title=Tribune Online Edition, May 4, 2002 |work=The Tribune |date=4 May 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys visit other schools and academies from time to time to take part in various tournaments. For skill improvement, the school often invites professional sports bodies to hold training camps, which are usually open to students from across India. In 2013, a football coaching camp was held in association with Bar\u00e7a Academy, the official training school of [[FC Barcelona]],<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/f-c-barcelona-at-doon-july-2013/</ref> and in January 2015, coaches from the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] held a week-long cricket training camp on the school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pitchvision.com/exclusive-inside-mcc-lords-club-india-coaching-camp-drills |title=Live Local Matches &#124; Tips & Techniques &#124; Articles & Podcasts |publisher=PitchVision |date=2017-07-24 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>http://educationworld.co/Magazines/EWIssueSection.aspx?Issue=September_2015&Section=Boarding_Schools&Article=India%27s_best_boys_boarding_school</ref>\n\n===Clubs and societies===\n{{See|The Doon School Model United Nations}}\n[[File:The Doon School Weekly.jpg|thumb|''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication of Doon. It is produced by the boys and distributed every Saturday morning.]]\n\nExtracurricular activities are also a compulsory element of school life.  There are around 70-80 clubs and societies, including astronomy, business, [[The Doon School Model United Nations]], quiz, photography and film, [[Model aircraft|aeromodelling]], robotics, paper recycling, weather reporting, pottery, carpentry, [[amateur radio]] and birdwatching, among others.<ref>{{cite web|author=\" + arr[2] + \" |url=https://www.outlookbusiness.com/cest-la-vie/the-good-life/a-class-act-5412 |title=Premium schools |publisher=Outlook Business |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> In many societies pupils come together to discuss a particular topic, presided over by a schoolmaster and often including a guest speaker. The school has often invited prominent figures to give speeches and talks to the students; these have included heads of state, politicians, ornithologists, naturalists, artists, writers, economists, diplomats and industrialists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/category/events/visiting-speakers/|title=Visiting Speakers Archives|website=Doon School}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/600-mn-to-be-enrolled-in-uidai-in-next-4-years-nilekani/714784 |title=600 Mn to be Enrolled in UIDAI in Next 4 Years: Nilekani |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nBoys can write for, or join the editorial board of, a number of school magazines that are published in English or Hindi. ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication and the official school newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/34/42/obituary/ |title=OBITUARY : Himalayan Journal vol.34/42 |publisher=Himalayanclub.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> Distributed every Saturday morning, and edited by pupils, it chronicles school activities and is a platform for creative, political or humorous writing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> The publication aims to represent the views of the school community as well as Old Boys, and include satire and criticism of school policies. More subversive publications, critical of teachers and the school establishment, have occasionally been produced without official sponsorship. Other magazines include ''The Yearbook'', a heavily illustrated publication for recording all highlights of the school year, and ''The Doon School Information Review'' for cultural criticism. Specialist publications by academic departments include '' Vibgyor'' (Art), ''Echo'' (Science), ''The Econocrat'' (Economics), ''Infinity'' (Mathematics), ''Grand Slam'' (Sports) and ''The Circle'' (History and Political Science).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/clubs-societies/publications/|title=Publications|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\n===Mountaineering===\n{{Main|Role of The Doon School in Indian mountaineering}}\n\n[[File:Mt. Everest Base Camp Expedition - 2008, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|2008 expedition to the [[Mount Everest Base Camp]] and [[Kala Patthar]].]]\n\nHalfway through each term, the boys go on a one-week \"midterm\", an expedition through the [[Siwalik Hills]] or [[Himalayas]]. Senior boys make treks of up to five days, unaccompanied by teachers, camping out in tents and cooking their own food. The trips are planned by students themselves. Alumni have recalled these midterms as being among their most formative and character-building experiences.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/how-the-playing-fields-of-doon-nurture-india-incs-best-leaders/articleshow/6872417.cms|title=How the playing fields of Doon nurture India Inc's best leaders |newspaper=The Times of India |date=5 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon has been credited with pioneering mountaineering in India, due to the accomplishments of masters such as [[R.L. Holdsworth]], [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], and alumni like [[Narendra Dhar Jayal|Nandu Jayal]], who later became the founder principal of [[Himalayan Mountaineering Institute]].<ref name=\"Kohli\"> {{cite book |last1=Kohli |first1=M.S. |title=Mountains of India: Tourism, Adventure and Pilgrimage |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Mountains_of_India.html?id=GIs4zv17HHwC&redir_esc=y |date=2002 |publisher=Indus |location= |language= |isbn=9788173871351 |pages= |chapter= |chapterurl= |page=209 |quote= p.290, Much of the credit for early interest in mountaineering among Indians goes to the Doon School, largely because of some distinguished British mountaineers on its staff like J.A.K. Martyn, J.T.M. Gibson, R.L. Holdsworth...In 1951, Gurdial Singh of the Doon School climbed the 7,120 metres high Trisul. This was the first Indian summit.}}</ref> Notable climbs by staff and alumni include [[Bandarpunch]] (6,316&nbsp;m) in 1950, Kala Nag (6,387&nbsp;m) in 1956, [[Trisul]] (7,120&nbsp;m) in 1951, [[Kamet]] (7,756&nbsp;m) in 1955, [[Abi Gamin]] (7,355&nbsp;m) in 1953 and 1955, Mrigthuni (6,855&nbsp;m) in 1958 and Jaonli (6,632 metres) in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/62/16/early-years-of-indian-mountaineering/ |title=Early Years of Indian Mountaineering |publisher=Himalayan Club |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> Some of these expeditions have been noted for their idiosyncrasies. After Gurdial Singh led a successful climb of Trisul, he performed a headstand [[asana]] on the summit as a tribute to the Hindu god [[Shiva]], who is said to abide there. Holdsworth smoked a pipe on reaching the summit of [[Kamet]] (7.756m), during its first ascent in 1931.<ref name=\"Harish Kapadia\"> {{cite book |last1=Kapadia |first1=Harish |title=Across Peaks and Passes in Garhwal Himalaya |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Across_Peaks_Passes_in_Garhwal_Himalaya.html?id=KptmxrqhKl4C |date=1999 |publisher=Indus Publishing |location=London |language=English |isbn=9788173870972 |page=17 |quote=The peak of Kamet was attempted several times and finally in 1931 Frank Smythe and Eric Shipton reached the summit along with some others. R.L. Holdsworth, who was with them, smoked a pipe on the summit, which I believe still remains a height record for smokers.}}</ref> Two Doon pupils climbed the [[Matterhorn]] in 1951 wearing cricket boots.<ref name=\"alpinejournal\">{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Richard|title=Climbing with the Doon School|journal=Alpine Journal|year=2001|pages=197\u2013201|url=http://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_2001_files/AJ%202001%20197-201%20Anderson%20Doon%20School.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre and music===\n[[File:Waiting for Godot in Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[Samuel Beckett]]'s ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' being staged in the Rose Bowl.]]\nAn [[amphitheatre]] known as the Rose Bowl was built largely by pupils in two years during the 1930s<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=130|quote=It took two years to complete the open air theatre. The first play staged on it was \"The Merchant of Venice prodcued by Jack Gibson, and he had all his actors dressed in Indian costumes.\"}}</ref> and underwent a major structural change in 2009.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Santayana|first=Vivek|title=Losing a Kidney|journal=The Doon School Weekly|date=24 October 2009|issue=2232|url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66UfGMuG8?url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It can seat up to 2,000 people and has been the setting for numerous [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] plays and other classics of western theatre, as well as musical performances and speeches during school ceremonies such as Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805061511/http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 August 2012 |title=Doon Online&nbsp;\u2013 Vikram Seth |publisher=Mtholyoke.edu |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The Multi-Purpose Hall is a more modern indoor theatre that can accommodate approximately 2,000 people. Plays are regularly staged in [[English language|English]] and [[Hindi]], with 8\u20139 productions each year including 2 major productions as part of the Founder's Day celebrations. The Inter House Once-Act Play competition is held each year, alternatively in English and Hindi. Many of the plays historically have been joint productions with the Welham Girls' School in [[Dehradun]].\n\nIn 2001 a new music school was built beside the Rose Bowl. It houses a [[music library]], a [[concert hall]] and several practice and teaching rooms where students learn various western and Indian instruments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/stas-and-activities/music/|title=Music Programme and Facilities at The Doon School|website=Doon School}}</ref> Pupils of the school have an option to appear for the [[Trinity Guildhall]] music examinations, conducted by [[Trinity College London]], in [[piano]], [[violin]], drums and classical guitar. In 2002 the school choir raised {{Indian Rupee}}2&nbsp;million for victims of the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake]] by organising a charity concert with the title ''Concerto 2000'', in which drummer [[Sivamani]] also took part.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/04/11/stories/2002041100070300.htm |title=Raga meets rhythm |newspaper=The Hindu |date=11 April 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/lf/2002/03/30/stories/2002033000930200.htm |title=Doon tunes |newspaper=The Hindu |date=30 March 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To commemorate its Platinum Jubilee, the school launched a music album called ''Spirit of Doon'' in collaboration with [[EMI]].<ref name=\"bare_url\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-14/news-and-interviews/28261521_1_music-album-doscos-alumni |title=Doon goes musical|newspaper=The Times of India |date=14 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The school choir sang two songs (\"Lab pe Aati Hai Dua\" and \"Anand Loke\") for the project but only the former was included in the final recording. The tracks were written by the lyricist [[Gulzar]] and were sung by [[Sonu Nigam]], Shayan Italia and [[Bhajan Sopori]].<ref name=\"bare_url\" />\n\n==Affiliations==\n\n===Ties with other schools===\n\nFrom its foundation in 1937 until the early 1980s, [[Welham Boys' School]] was a [[feeder school]] for Doon School and Mayo College.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/31886-welham-boys-school-to-celebrate-platinum-jubilee-year.html |title=Welham Boys' School to celebrate platinum jubilee year |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> This ended when Surendra Kandhari, an old boy and former housemaster at Doon, became Principal of Welham and transformed it into a high school. Several families who send their sons to Doon send their daughters to [[Welham Girls' School]], and many Doon alumni have married alumnae of Welham.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070121/ttlife1.htm |title=The Tribune Lifestyle |newspaper=The Tribune |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The two schools hold an annual \"dance social\", and their alumni sometimes collaborate in organising events. Pakistani ex-pupils from Doon established the [[Chand Bagh School]] 40&nbsp;km north of [[Lahore]], Pakistan, in 1998, modelling it on the general structure of Doon.<ref>{{cite web|author=Azhar M. A. Qureshi |url=http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611010826/http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 June 2009 |title=Chand Bagh School |publisher=Chandbagh.edu.pk |accessdate=24 January 2012 }}</ref> Doon also has exchange programmes with a number of overseas schools, such as Eton College, Harrow School, [[St. Albans School (Washington, D.C.)|St. Albans School, Washington DC]], [[Millfield]], [[Schule Schloss Salem]], [[The Armidale School]], [[Bridge House School]], [[Deerfield Academy]], [[King's Academy]], [[Stowe School]], [[Scotch College, Melbourne]], [[The Hutchins School]] and [[St. Mark's School (Texas)]]. In 2011 Doon twinned with [[The Thomas Hardye School]], Dorchester, [[England]], through a cultural exchange project organised by the [[BBC]] and [[British Council]] in light of the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] held in the [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9451296.stm|title=Schools Spotlight on Team Abhinav Bindra|publisher=BBC|date=8 April 2011|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Schools with similar names===\nAs private schools became more widespread in [[India]], several other schools used \"Doon\" as part of their names, causing some confusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-using-doon-in-their-names-to-cash-the-popularity-of-the-doon-school/articleshow/69224014.cms |title=Schools using Doon in their names to cash the popularity of The Doon School &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Among them are Doon Global School, Doon Presidency School, [[Doon International School (Palia Kalan)|Doon International School]], Doon Preparatory School, Doon Cambridge School, Doon Girls School, [[Doon Public School]] (in West Delhi, not the Doon Valley) and the Doon College of Spoken English. None of them are related to The Doon School.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-10-24/special-report/28263544_1_doon-school-ipsc-sainik-schools |title=Is the old school tie wearing thin?|newspaper=The Times of India |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Memberships===\nThe Doon School is a member of following organisations: [[G20 Schools]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Gold |first=Adam |url=http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028073515/http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 October 2007 |title=Move over G8\u2014this is G20 > Harvard Westlake Chronicle Online |publisher=Students.hw.com |date=8 November 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Round Square]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925000935/http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 September 2012 |title=Doon School India |publisher=RoundSquare |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Interact Club|Rotary International's Interact Club]], [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmc.org.uk/schools/the-doon-school/ |title=HMC Schools : International Members |publisher=Hmc.org.uk |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[International Boys' Schools Coalition]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theibsc.org/page.cfm?p=38&filter_data7=&filter_data10=INDIA&filter_data13=&filter_data15=&key=&submit=SEARCH |title=International Boys' Schools Coalition: Member Directory |publisher=Theibsc.org |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examinations]], [[International Baccalaureate|International Baccalaureate Organization (IBO)]], Indian Public Schools' Conference,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802223143/http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 August 2012 |title=Indian Public Schools' Conference |publisher=Ipsc.co.in |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Rashtriya Life Saving Society (India)]], [[International Award Association]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Pioneer |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/doon-school-becomes-first-indian-school-to-start-iayp-online.html |title=Doon School becomes first Indian school to start IAYP online |publisher=Dailypioneer.com |date=2014-08-06 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe school is the regional test centre for [[University of Cambridge ESOL Examinations]] and [[SAT]] Tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ivyzone.com/category/sat/test-centre/ |title=SAT l STUDY ABROAD l VISA I IvyZone.com &#124; Test-centre |publisher=Ivyzone.com |date=22 March 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public image==\n;Doon in films & television\n{{main|Dazed in Doon}}\n{{main|Indian Summer School}}\n\n* The film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'', which was commissioned by the School on the occasion of its 75th anniversary and produced by old boy Ashvin Kumar, was banned by the school authorities because it \"doesn't give the school a good name\". The dispute remains unresolved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-path-not-taken/article2924231.ece|title=The path not taken|first=Sudhish|last=Kamath|date=23 February 2012|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n* In September 2010, [[BBC Sport]] made a documentary on the Doon School for the ''World Olympic Dreams'' Project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9075650.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 The school that breeds Indian medal winners |publisher=BBC News |date=11 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The documentary was produced in association with the [[British Council]]. Its main purpose was to show the school where [[Abhinav Bindra]], the first Indian individual Olympic gold medallist, spent his formative years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 Abhinav Bindra, India |publisher=BBC News |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n* In 2017, [[Channel 4]] of UK commissioned a 3-part documentary, ''[[Indian Summer School]]'', where working-class boys from the UK were given a chance to study at Doon for a term to see if they would benefit from the all-round experience of an Indian residential school. The filming began in August 2017, and the programmes were broadcast in March\u2013April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/mar/29/indian-summer-school-review-five-terrible-teens-are-sent-to-indias-equivalent-of-eton |title=Indian Summer School review \u2013 five terrible teens are sent to India\u2019s equivalent of Eton &#124; Television & radio |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n;Doon in literature\n* [[Vikram Seth]] used his own experiences of being bullied at Doon to model the character of Tapan in ''[[A Suitable Boy]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Huang |first1=Guiyou |title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Asian American Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/The_Greenwood_Encyclopedia_of_Asian_Amer.html?id=d5RxDwAAQBAJ |date=2009 |publisher=[[Greenwood Press]] |location=Westport, Connecticut |language= |isbn=9781567207361 |page=860 |quote=...as a boarder at the prestigious Doon School, known as \"the Eton of India\" on Dehradun. Whilst at school, Seth encountered abuse and bullying from many of his fellow classmates, an experience that he later evokes by the character Tapan, the youngest of the Chaterjees, in ''A Suitable Boy''.}}</ref>\n* In [[Salman Rushdie]]'s short-story anthology [[East, West]], the protagonists Zulu and Chekhov are Doscos.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Damrosch |first1=David |title=How to Read World Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/How_to_Read_World_Literature.html?id=1VYsDwAAQBAJ |date=2017 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Son]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781119009245 |page=172 |quote=Chekhov and Zulu became ''Star Trek'' devotees while still in school in India...Significantly, they are enrolled in the Doon School, an elite British-style academy established in the waning years of British Raj.}}</ref>\n* In [[Tenzing Norgay]]'s autobiography ''Man of Everest'', he refers to [[Bandarpunch]] as \"The Doon School mountain\" due to the fact that the mountain was frequented by two Doon School teachers [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John Martyn]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Norgay |first1=Tenzing |title=Man of Everest \u2013 The Autobiography of Tenzing |url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=90IPAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=doon+school+mountain |date=1955 |publisher=[[George G. Harrap and Co.]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781447400288 |page=154 |quote= It was to Garhwal. Back to Bandar Punch, \"the Doon School mountain,\" with my old friend Mr Gibson. }}</ref>\n* In [[Ruskin Bond]]'s novella ''Strangers in the Night'', character Jai Shankar is from Doon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bond |first1=Ruskin |title=Strangers in the Night |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Strangers_on_the_Roof.html?id=58nqMgEACAAJ |date=1994 |publisher=[[Penguin Books India]] |location= |language= |isbn=9780140240658 |page=4 |quote=William and Jai did not trail me to this place, as it was a little lowbrow for them (William being Swiss and Jai being Doon School.}}</ref>\n* [[Penguin Books|Penguin's]] ''The Great Speeches of Modern India'' (2011) included Vikram Seth's 1992 Founder's Day address, which being confessional surprised the school community, and [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]]'s 2007 speech, which was noted for its wit and humour.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z7dCH_IYbt8C&q=doon+school#v=snippet&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=The Great Speeches of Modern India - Rudranghsu Mukherjee - Google Books |date= October 2011|accessdate=16 July 2017|isbn=9788184002348 |last1=Mukherjee |first1=Rudranghsu }}</ref>\n\n;Doon in research\n* ''Doon School Chronicles'' is the first of five [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] films called the ''Doon School Quintet'', made by David MacDougall between 1997 and 2000 about the culture of the School.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://raifilm.org.uk/films/doon-school-chronicles/|title=Film : \u201cDoon School Chronicles\u201d \u2013 RAI Ethnographic Film Catalogue}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220001143/http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 February 2006 |title=Berkeley Media LLC: Catalog: Doon School Chronicles |publisher=Berkeleymedia.com |accessdate=20 February 2012 }}</ref> Macdougall has written of a tendency of some alumni to idealise a ''[[Golden age (metaphor)|Golden Age]]'' set in the first decade of the school's life, which sometimes makes them resistant to change.<ref name=\"MacDougall2006-p107-108\">{{citation|last=MacDougall|first=David|title=The corporeal image: film, ethnography, and the senses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&pg=PA107|accessdate=31 March 2012|year=2006|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-12156-7|pages=107\u2013108}}</ref><ref>{{cite video|first=David|last=MacDougall|url=http://www.roninfilms.com.au/feature/526/doon-school-chronicles.html |title=DOON SCHOOL CHRONICLES|publisher=Ronin Films|accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School'' by Sanjay Srivastva is a detailed [[Sociology|sociological]] study of the school's culture and how it has influenced India's national character.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva}}</ref>\n* ''{{'}}Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools'', a 2005 report by the Institute of Social Studies Trust, discusses why the Doon School has no [[Reservation in India|reservations]] (quotas for specific social groups) in its admissions process. The post quotes an unnamed student who explains, \"passing the Doon School entrance exam means that you have proved yourself worthy of the school. Reserving seats for students seems to imply that the school must prove itself worthy of you.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Mallica |title='Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools |url=http://www.isst-india.org/PDF/Poor%20children%20in%20Rich%20school.pdf |publisher=Institute of Social Studies Trust |accessdate=30 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=February 2017}}</ref>\n* In 1969, [[Asian Survey]] (then Asian Review) - an Asian studies [[academic journal]] of [[University of California, Berkeley]] - produced a report on The Doon School as a part of their project which documented Indian history after the entry of [[East India Company]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sh4sAQAAIAAJ&q=doon+school&dq=doon+school |title=Asian review&nbsp;\u2014 Demetrius Charles Boulger, East India Association (London, England), Oriental Institute (Woking, England)  |accessdate=30 March 2013|last1=Boulger |first1=Demetrius Charles |year=1969 }}</ref>\n* In ''Indian Tales of the Raj'', Zareer Masani studies how Doon School's alumni affected the Indian political scene in the '60s.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Lm4FVb54_oUC&pg=PA152&dq=doon+school#v=onepage&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=Indian Tales of the Raj&nbsp;\u2014 Zareer Masani  |accessdate=30 March 2013|isbn=9780520071278 |last1=Masani |first1=Zareer |year=1988 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n\n\n{{Main|List of The Doon School alumni}}\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School alumni}}\n[[File:Vikram Seth, in Oxfordshire.jpg|thumb|right|175px|[[Vikram Seth]] (Class of 1969), novelist and poet, author of ''[[A Suitable Boy]]'' and ''[[The Golden Gate]]''.]]\n\nPupils are known as \"Doscos\", a contraction of \"Doon\" and \"school\". The vast majority of alumni are Indians, but a dwindling number are from Pakistan having studied at Doon before the [[Partition of India]] forced them to leave in 1947. Relations between Indian and Pakistani alumni have remained warm over the years, despite the long history of conflict between the two countries.<ref name=\"tribuneindia.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101024/dplus.htm#2 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys from Bangladesh and Nepal continue to study at Doon. Pupils of Doon have achieved prominence in politics, government service, the armed forces of India and Pakistan, commerce, journalism, the arts and literature.<ref name=\"suitablejoy\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/1999/mar/27/books.guardianreview1 |title=A suitable joy|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 March 1999 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes1993\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/02/magazine/vikram-seth-s-big-book.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |title=Vikram Seth's Big Book&nbsp;\u2013 New York Times |work=The New York Times |date=2 May 1993 |accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref> They include [[Union Cabinet of India|cabinet ministers]], [[Chief minister (India)|chief ministers]], several members of the [[Parliament of India|Indian Parliament]] and [[Legislative Assembly|state Legislative Assemblies]], diplomats, and former heads of the Indian and Pakistani Air Forces.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/06/01/stories/2009060153270700.htm |title=Other States / Uttaranchal News : Seven Doon alumni in 15th Lok Sabha |newspaper=The Hindu |date=1 June 2009 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Former Prime Minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]] was educated at Doon.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/13/magazine/mrs-gandhi-grooms-another-son.html|title=Mrs. Gandhi Grooms Another Son|first=Michael T.|last=Kaufman|date=13 June 1982|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n[[File:Sanjit Bunker Roy at Time 2010.jpg|thumb|left|160px|[[Bunker Roy]] (Class of 1962), social activist and the founder of [[Barefoot College]], [[Tilonia]].]]\nNotable Doon alumni to have held senior positions in Indian and Pakistani politics include the former Indian diplomat turned politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]], the former Defence Secretary of Pakistan [[Ghulam Jilani Khan]], [[Kamal Nath]], [[Rahul Gandhi]], [[Sanjay Gandhi]], [[Chief Minister of Odisha ]] [[Naveen Patnaik]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]], politican and poet [[Karan Singh]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Allana |first=Alia |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/doon-squad/464930/ |title=The Doon School Squad|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> In the field of literature, Doon alumni include novelists [[Amitav Ghosh]], [[Vikram Seth]], [[Ardashir Vakil]], and historian [[Ramachandra Guha]];<ref>{{cite news|author=Elisabeth Bumiller |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/29/books/a-novelist-beginning-with-a-bang.html |title=A Novelist Beginning With a Bang - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1997-07-29 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> and in journalism, [[Prannoy Roy]], founder of [[NDTV]]; [[Aroon Purie]], founder of ''[[India Today]]'', [[Karan Thapar]], [[Virendra Prabhakar]] and [[Vikram Chandra (NDTV)|Vikram Chandra]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/microsoft-s-new-boss-is-a-window-on-a-better-school-system-9115621.html|title=Microsoft\u2019s new boss is a window on a better school system|date=7 February 2014|website=The Independent}}</ref> India's first [[Rhodes scholar]], [[Lovraj Kumar]], was an alumnus.<ref>{{cite news|author=I. M. D. Little |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-lovraj-kumar-1367199.html |title=Obituary: Lovraj Kumar|newspaper=The Independent |date=1 April 1994 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Abhinav Bindra]], India's first Olympic gold medallist, and the mountaineer [[Nandu Jayal]] studied at the school.<ref>{{cite news|author=BBC Sports Desk |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=Abhinav Bindra Indian Olympic Medallist|publisher=BBC |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Anish Kapoor at the Deutsche Guggenheim - Berlin.jpg|thumb|right|170px|[[Anish Kapoor]] (Class of 1970), artist. Designs include Chicago's [[Cloud Gate]] and [[ArcelorMittal Orbit]], [[Olympic Park, London]].]] In the field of arts and entertainment, Doon's alumni include [[Ali Fazal]], [[Roshan Seth]], [[Himani Shivpuri]], [[Chandrachur Singh]], [[Satyadeep Mishra]], and art collector [[Abhishek Poddar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christies.com/features/The-Abhishek-and-Radhika-Poddar-collection-of-Indian-Modern-and-Contemporary-Art-7960-1.aspx |title=How Abhishek and Radhika Poddar built their collection of Indian art &#124; Christie's |publisher=Christies.com |date=2016-12-18 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The [[Turner Prize]]-winning sculptor [[Anish Kapoor]] and [[Vivan Sundaram]] also attended Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/jun/07/anish-kapoor-sculpture-versailles-controversy |title=Anish Kapoor: superstar sculptor who loves to court scandal &#124; Observer profile &#124; Art and design |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> In business, the Doon alumni include [[Analjit Singh]] of Max Group, [[Sunil Kant Munjal]], chairman of [[Hero MotoCorp]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2013/10/28/the-doon-school-grooming-ground-for-indias-wealthy-kids/|title=The Doon School: Grooming Ground For India's Wealthy Kids|first=Forbes|last=Staff|website=Forbes}}</ref> [[Rahul Akerkar]], restaurateur and founder of Indigo and Qualia; father and son [[Vikram Lal]] and [[Siddhartha Lal]] of [[Eicher Motors]]; [[A. Vellayan]], chairman of the [[Murugappa Group]], [[Ajit Narain Haksar]], the first Indian chairman of [[ITC Limited]]; [[R.C. Bhargava]], chairman of [[Maruti Suzuki]]; [[Ajay S. Shriram]], managing director of [[DCM Shriram group]], and [[Sharan Pasricha]], CEO of Ennismore hospitality developer and founder of [[The Hoxton]] and [[Gleneagles Hotel|Gleneagles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/gleneagles-is-a-sleeping-giant-well-make-it-the-best-hotel-in-the-world-lbhjf75z0|title=\u2018Gleneagles is a sleeping giant. We\u2019ll make it the best hotel in the world\u2019|first=Dominic|last=Walsh|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Faculty===\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School faculty}}\nIn the early years, many teachers came from British schools, including [[Peter Lawrence (teacher)|Peter Lawrence]] from Eton College,<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4309213.stm|title=Eton, the Raj and modern India|date=9 March 2005|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] from [[Ripon Grammar School]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20041207/edit.htm|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Opinions|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref> [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John A. K. Martyn]] and [[R. L. Holdsworth]] from Harrow.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> The school's first art teacher was the artist [[Sudhir Khastgir]], from [[Visva-Bharati University|Shantiniketan]], who joined in 1936 and remained at school for twenty years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?267708 |title=Bonfire of Vanities &#124; Vishvjit P. Singh |publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> Many sculptures and murals on the campus today were created by him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jnaf.org/artist/sudhir-khastgir/|title=Sudhir Khastgir - JNAF}}</ref> The film director [[Chetan Anand (director)|Chetan Anand]] taught briefly at the school from 1940 to 1944.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/arts/dev-anand-chetan-anand-doon-school-dehradun/story/1/19703.html|title=How Doon School inspired the inimitable Dev Anand style|website=www.dailyo.in}}</ref> Mountaineer [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]] joined in 1946 as a geography teacher and led the boys on many expeditions.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/50-years-later-its-happily-Everest-after/articleshow/46893756.cms|title=50 years later, it's happily Everest after &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The cricketer and mathematics teacher, [[Sheel Vohra]], joined in 1959 and became the longest-serving master in school's history when he retired in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/remembering-sheel-vohra-doon-schools-beloved-bond.html|title=Remembering Sheel Vohra, Doon School's beloved 'Bond'|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> The [[Fiji-Indian]] academic [[Satendra Nandan]] taught history at school in the early 1960s, and the [[sarod]] player [[Ashok Roy]] headed the music department from 1977 to 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijisun.com.fj/2014/10/25/its-time-goodbye-comrades/|title=It's Time: Goodbye, COMRADES - Fiji Sun|publisher=}}</ref> [[Popular science]] author and theoretical physicist, [[Simon Singh]], taught science at Doon in 1987 before embarking on his academic and writing career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/there-s-math-in-simpsons-simon-says/story-czEcewcbqXaAuE38U6oF2K.html|title=There's math in Simpsons, Simon says|date=11 January 2014|work=[[Hindustan Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Schools|Education}}\n* [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://archive.is/20121219012747/http://fullcirclebooks.in/content/chhota-hazri-days-doscos-yatra ''Chhota Hazri Days: A Dosco's Yatra''] by Sanjiv Bathla, [[Rupa & Co.]], 2010 {{ISBN|978-81-291-1694-9}}.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130323003553/http://www.penguinbooksindia.com/en/content/sahibs-who-loved-india ''Sahibs who Loved India''] by [[Khushwant Singh]], [[Penguin Books]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-14-341580-0}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&q=Doon+School&dq=the+doon+school+sixty+years+on+pushpinder&source=gbs_word_cloud_r&cad=5#v=snippet&q=Doon%20School&f=false ''The Corporeal Image''] by David McDougall, [[Princeton University Press]], 2006, {{ISBN|978-0-691-12156-7}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Trees of Chandbagh''] by K.C. Sinha, Konark Publishers, 1996, {{ISBN|978-81-220-0457-1}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=3sVlHQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''For Hills To Climb''] by Gurdial Singh and Nalni Dhar, The Doon School Old Boys' Society, 2001.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=NEdmQgAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Doon, The Story of a School''], IPSS (1985) edited by Sumer Singh, published by the Indian Public Schools Society 1985. ASIN B0006ENF66\n* [http://dsobs.net/currentrb/current_rosebowl.php ''The Rose Bowl''],  a periodic newsletter by the Doon School Old Boys' Society\n* [https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School, ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School''] by Sanjay Srivastva, published by [[Routledge]] 1998 {{ISBN|0-203-98027-1}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |n=no |q=The Doon School |s=Category:The Doon School |v=no |species=no |commons=Category:The Doon School }}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.doonschool.com/|name = Official website}}\n* [http://www.dsobs.net/ Website of the Doon School Old Boys' Society]\n* [http://store.doonschool.com/ The Doon School - Gift Store]\n\n{{The Doon School}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doon School}}\n[[Category:The Doon School| ]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Round Square schools]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in India]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in India]]\n[[Category:Cambridge schools in India]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Schools in Dehradun]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1935]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{in use}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2016}}\n{{short description|Boys' boarding school in Dehradun, India}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n | image                   = The Doon School.jpg\n | caption                 = Main Building at The Doon School\n | image_size              = 300px\n | name                    = The Doon School\n | logo                    = The Doon School, Dehradun - logo.png\n | logo_size               = 150px\n | colours                 = Blue & White {{color box|#005293}} {{color box|white}}\n | coordinates             = {{Coord|30.333|78.030|type:edu_region:IN|display=title}}\n | pushpin_map             = India Uttarakhand#India\n | location                = The Doon School<br>Mall Road<br>[[Dehradun]]&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;248001<br>India<br>([https://www.google.co.in/maps/place/The+Doon+School/@30.3350253,78.0298105,17z Google Map], [https://www.openstreetmap.org/way/158385701 OpenStreetMap])\n | specialist              = \n | schooltype              = Private [[boarding school]]\n | motto                   = '' Knowledge our Light''\n | sister_school           = [[Welham Girls' School]]\n | established             = \n | founded                 = {{Start date and age|1935|09|10}}\n | founder                 = [[Satish Ranjan Das]]\n | head_name               = Founder Headmaster\n | head                    = [[Arthur Foot|Arthur Edward Foot]]\n | gender                  = Boys\n | lower_age               = 12\n | upper_age               = 18\n | headmaster              = Post vacant \n | chair_label             = Chairman of Governors\n | chair                   = [[Sunil Kant Munjal]]\n | pupils                  = c. 600\n | faculty                 = 70\n | houses                  = 5 houses + 2 holding houses\n | campus                  = 72 acres (297,314&nbsp;m\u00b2)\n | ceeb                    = 671616\n | district                = [[Dehradun district|Dehradun District]]\n | student_union           = [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n | affiliation             = [[International Baccalaureate|IB]]<br>[[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examination|CISCE]]<br>[[International General Certificate of Secondary Education|IGCSE]]\n | publication             = ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]''\n | free_label2             = Annual fees\n | free_text2              = {{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1025000}} (home students)<br>{{Indian Rupee}}{{formatnum:1281000}} (international)\n | free_label              = Former pupils\n | free_text               = [[List of The Doon School alumni|Doscos]]\n | website                 = [http://www.doonschool.com/ www.doonschool.com]\n}}\n\n'''The Doon School''' (informally '''Doon School''' or '''Doon''') is a boys-only private [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit]], [[Selective school|selective]] boarding school in Dehradun, Uttarakhand, India, established in 1935. It was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a [[Kolkata]] lawyer, who prevised a school modelled on the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[public school (United Kingdom)|public school]], but conscious of Indian ambitions and desires. Although he died in 1928, he is considered the founder of the school. The school's first [[Head teacher|headmaster]] was [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], an Englishman who had spent nine years as a science master at [[Eton College]], England.<ref>{{cite book|year=1979|chapter=FOOT, Arthur Edward|title=Who Was Who 1961\u20131970|location=London|publisher=A. & C. Black|isbn=0-7136-2008-0}}</ref> The last headmaster was [[Matthew Raggett]], who resigned in January 2020. He was the fourth British headmaster in Doon's history and a member of [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]], [[UK]].\n\nThe school houses roughly 500 pupils aged 12 to 18, and admission is based on a competitive entrance examination, a group discussion and an interview with the headmaster. Every year in January and April, the school admits pupils aged 13 in Grade 7 (known as D-form) and aged 14 in Grade 8 (C-form) respectively. Boys take the [[IGCSE]] exam in Grade 10, and for the final two years can choose between [[Indian School Certificate]] or [[International Baccalaureate]] curriculum. Doon remains a boys-only school despite continued pressure from political leaders, including former [[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]], to become [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]]. [[Old boy network|Old boys]] of the school are known as 'Doscos'. \n\nDoon has been consistently ranked the best all-boys residential school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/17-schools-from-u---khand-secure-top-10-positions-in-ewisr.html|title=17 schools from U\u2019khand secure Top 10 positions in EWISR|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> Although the school has often been cited as 'Eton of India' by media outlets such as the [[BBC]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02c3zgq|title=BBC World Service - Witness, India's Eton|website=BBC}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|author=STEVEN R. WEISMAN, Special to the New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/11/12/world/india-s-old-school-tie-harrow-by-the-himalayas.html |title=India'S Old School Tie - Harrow By The Himalayas |location=Dehra Dun (India); India |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=12 November 1985 |accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/aug/13/fiction.arundhatiroy|title=The lost sub-continent|first=William|last=Dalrymple|date=13 August 2005|website=the Guardian}}</ref> ''[[The Spectator]]'',<ref name=\"Spectator UK\">{{cite web|author=Read |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/03/its-a-spartan-life-at-the-eton-of-india/# |title=It's a spartan life at 'the Eton of India' |publisher=The Spectator |date= |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/alastair-sooke/7546719/The-rise-and-rise-of-Anish-Kapoor-Inc..html|title=The rise & rise of Anish Kapoor Inc.|first=Alastair|last=Sooke|date=2 April 2010|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> and ''[[Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite web|last=Remnick |first=David |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1987/10/20/rajiv-gandhi-and-the-mantle-unsought/779cee82-b666-4248-8116-278d6134a002/ |title=Rajiv Gandhi And The Mantle Unsought |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1987-10-20 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> it strongly eschews the label.<ref name=\"Spectator UK\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/sunday-times/deep-focus/Doon-of-India-wants-to-conquer-the-globe/articleshow/6800690.cms |title=\u2018Doon of India\u2019 wants to conquer the globe - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2010-10-24 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has educated a wide range of notable alumni, including politicians, diplomats, artists, writers and business leaders.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref name=\"articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709213757/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-12-30/news/27356038_1_doon-school-dosco-wannabe |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 July 2012 |title=For wannabe Doons, don from hills is a boon |newspaper=Times of India |date=30 December 2002 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> Among the former pupils of Doon are the late Indian prime minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]], artist [[Anish Kapoor]], novelists [[Vikram Seth]] and [[Amitav Ghosh]], fashion designer [[Tarun Tahiliani]], mountaineer [[Nandu Jayal]] and social activist [[Bunker Roy]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\n[[File:The Doon School main building (then FRI) - 1917.jpg|thumb|250px|Main building of Doon in 1917, when it was part of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]].]]\n[[File:Main Gate, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main gate of the Doon School.]]\nDoon was envisioned by [[Satish Ranjan Das]], a lawyer from Calcutta and advocate-general of Bengal, who in 1927 became a member of the [[Viceroy's Executive Council]] of [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Irwin]] on the condition that he would use the prestige of this position to raise funds for a new type of school in [[India]].<ref name=\"auto\">MacDougall2006, p.100</ref> He decided to name the new school \"Doon\", as it was situated in the [[Doon Valley]]. He travelled widely in [[India]] with the goal of collecting {{Indian Rupee}}4&nbsp;million, but at the time of his death had raised only {{Indian Rupee}}1 million in cash and a further {{Indian Rupee}}1&nbsp;million in promises.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |pages=360 |jstor=41364317}}</ref>  With the money, Das formed the Indian Public Schools' Society (IPSS), which had the objective of founding new public schools in [[India]] that would admit students regardless of caste, creed or social status. Under the IPSS, a Board of Governors supervises all matters of Doon.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 41: \"...the body founded by Das for the purposes of establishing the Doon School, the Indian Public Schools Society\"</ref>\n\nAfter the death of Das in 1928, the IPSS accomplished little, and by 1934 some of the original lenders had begun to inquire about the return of their money.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |pages=360 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> To solve this problem, Sir Joseph Bhore, then Railway Minister of [[Freeman Freeman-Thomas, 1st Marquess of Willingdon|Lord Willingdon's]] Council, became IPSS chairman and, with [[Akbar Hydari|Sir Akbar Hydari]] as secretary, worked to obtain the former estate of the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] in [[Dehra Dun]] on favourable terms.<ref>''The Indian Year Book'', vol. 29 (1942), p. 419: \"Doon School&nbsp;\u2013 This school which is established in the Chand Bagh and Skinner's Estates at Dehra Doon owes its origin to the initiative and enthusiasm of the late SR Das.\"</ref> Sir Frank Noyce also joined the team. [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Halifax]], then President of the British Board of Education, led a selection committee that nominated [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], a science teacher at [[Eton College]], to be the first headmaster. On 27 October 1935, the [[Viceroy]], [[Lord Willingdon]], presided over the formal opening of the school. Seventy boys enrolled in the first [[Academic term|term]], and 110 more signed up for the second.<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 203 (Note 12): \"...from Willingdon's inaugural address on 27 October 1935\"</ref> \n\n===Early years:1935\u20131970===\n\nFoot had never visited [[India]] before accepting the position of headmaster. He noted that the school appeared to be surrounded by forests and close to mountains, and the possibilities of outdoor recreation and mountaineering seem to have influenced his decision as much as the chance to create a completely new type of school in [[India]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |pages=359 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> Foot's first action upon being offered the position was to recruit [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J.A.K. (John) Martyn]] from [[Harrow School]] as his deputy. Doon's ethos and guiding principles were determined early in its life by Foot, Martyn, [[R. L. Holdsworth|R.L. Holdsworth]] and [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]], who went on to become principal of [[Mayo College]].<ref>{{cite web|author=site admin |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/society-the-arts/books/story/19851115-book-review-sumer-singh-doon-the-story-of-a-school-mady-martyn-martyn-sahib-802174-2014-01-16 |title=Where East meets West - Society & The Arts News - Issue Date: Nov 15, 1985 |publisher=Indiatoday.in |date=1985-11-15 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> They were soon joined in their efforts by Indians such as the artist [[Sudhir Khastgir]] (the school's first art teacher, who had trained previously in [[Santiniketan]]) and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], a noted mountaineer who taught at Doon for several decades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> In an essay entitled ''The Objects of Education'' published in the school magazine, Foot offered a template for a complete education for boys, which included teaching them to form a habit of choosing good over evil, think logically, express their thoughts and views clearly, and maintain a healthy body.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\" /> \n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  =...&nbsp;By 14 he should have learnt all the ordinary principles of social behaviour. He should know how to stand up and speak to a variety of different types of people&nbsp;\u2013 to his own mother, to someone else's mother, to his father, to his schoolmasters, to servants, to Mahatma Gandhi or to the Viceroy, and to do this without any self-consciousness&nbsp;...At 17 must come another quality, less instinctive and requiring a maturer mind: he must acquire a capacity of judgement.<ref name=\"sixtyyears\">{{cite book|title=The Doon School Sixty Years On |publisher=Doon School Old Boys' Society|date=October 1996}}</ref>&nbsp;...\n |source = <small>Arthur Foot, 1946, ''The Objects of Education''</small>\n |align  = left\n |width  = 30%\n}}\n\nThe annual school fees in 1935 was {{Indian Rupee}}1,375, and by September 1946, it had risen to {{Indian Rupee}}1,800.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |pages=360 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> In 1947, there were around 300 boys studying at Doon, out of which 50-60 were [[Muslims]], 15-20 [[Sikhs]], 15-20 [[Parsees]], 6-7 Christians, and the remaining two-thirds Hindu.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |pages=365 |jstor=41364317}}</ref> Martyn, who became the second headmaster in 1948, acknowledged the influence of German educator [[Kurt Hahn]] in the development of the school's ethos. Although Martyn had not visited India before, he immediately accepted Foot's offer because of the opportunity it afforded to implement Hahn's ideas, which he had not been able to do at Harrow.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=38|quote=When John wrote to Hahn to tell him we was going to India, Hahn replied that he had been waiting to be able to offer him a place at Gordonstoun...}}</ref> While Foot and Martyn were determined to model Doon on Eton and Harrow, they both agreed that Doon should cater primarily for Indian boys\u2014and not the sons of British expatriates\u2014in order to create a uniquely Indian public school rather than a transplanted British institution. Foot did not want Doon to be considered elitist. At the opening of the school, he said, \"Our boys will join an aristocracy, but it\u2019s an aristocracy of service inspired by ideals of unselfishness, not one of wealth, privilege or position\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/academy/interview_doon-school-is-popular-for-building-an-aristocracy-of-service_1392063 |title=Doon School is popular for building an 'aristocracy of service'&nbsp;\u2013 Academy|work=DNA |date=5 June 2010 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> In a paper surveying the new school, presented to the [[Royal Society of Arts]], London in 1947, Foot wrote: \"In language we have never intended to base our instruction on the Classics in the way that Latin is still the centre pin of the English Public School. The great majority of boys take Urdu or Hindi.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Foot |first1=A.E. |date=April 1947 |title=The Doon School ||journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Arts]] |volume=95 |issue=4741 |pages=361 |jstor=41364317}}</ref>\n\n===Middle years: 1970\u20132000===\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; clear:left; margin-right:1em; font-size:85%; background:#ffc; color:black; width:20em; max-width:25%;\" cellspacing=\"5\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Headmasters\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n* [[Arthur Foot|Arthur E. Foot]], 1935\u20131948\n* [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|J. A. K. Martyn]], 1948\u20131966\n* [[C. J. Miller]], 1966\u20131970\n* [[Eric Simeon|Eric J. Simeon]], 1970\u20131979\n* [[Gulab Ramchandani]], 1979\u20131988\n* [[Shomie Das]], 1988\u20131996\n* [[John Mason (Schoolmaster)|John A. Mason]], 1996\u20132003\n* [[Kanti Bajpai]], 2003\u20132009\n* [[Peter McLaughlin]], 2009\u20132016\n* [[Matthew Raggett]], 2016\u20132020 \n|}\n\nThe school's first Indian headmaster was [[Eric Simeon]], appointed in 1970. He came from a military background and laid great emphasis on disciplined living.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/schooled-for-life/32471/|title=Schooled for life - Indian Express|website=archive.indianexpress.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/05/16/stories/2007051615082000.htm |title=Lt. Col. Eric Joseph Simeon dead |work=The Hindu |date=16 May 2007 |accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> Simeon's tenure of nine years was marked with financial difficulties for the school and the estate suffered, as the funds were not enough to maintain buildings and facilities. <ref>https://www.doonschool.com/weekly/May%2019%202007.pdf</ref> In 1971, Simeon introduced the 'Scholar's Blazer', an academic equivalent of the pre-existing prize 'Games Blazer', so that boys accorded academic excellence the same level of prestige as they did sporting achievements.<ref name=\"Back to School\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/KaranThapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104092100/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/karanthapar/Back-to-school/Article1-617070.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 November 2010 |last=Thapar|first=Karan|title=Back to School |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1979, [[Gulab Ramchandani]] became the first alumnus to be appointed headmaster, and during his term the school regained financial stability.<ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/ramchandani-old-boy-and-workaholic-headmaster-who-transformed-doon-school/articleshow/58185206.cms</ref> In 1988, [[Shomie Das]], another alumnus and the grandson of school founder Satish Ranjan Das, became headmaster. Das's focus was on upgrading the school infrastructure, and the Oberoi house was added to the original four houses. The next headmaster, [[John Mason (schoolmaster)|John Mason]], appointed in 1996, planned on making Doon more affordable to school pupils. The school did not raise its fees while Mason was in office. \n\n====Criticism of Rajiv Gandhi administration====\n\nIn the 1980s, the then [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Rajiv Gandhi]], an alumnus, drew criticism from the media for appointing many old boys to his administration. His inner circle was labelled a \"Doon cabinet\" or \"Dosco Mafia\"<ref>''Indian Tales of the Raj'' by Zareer Masani, p.152</ref> and ''Washington Post'' reported, \"The catch phrase around Delhi these days is that the 'Doon School runs India,' but that is too simple an analysis for a complex, chaotic country with so many competing spheres of influence.\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\">{{cite web|last=Bumiller |first=Elisabeth |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/1985/11/24/where-indias-elite-were-boys-together/0579f3d9-1835-4441-b1b1-a55e3111bdc3/ |title=Where India's Elite Were Boys Together |publisher=The Washington Post |date=1985-11-24 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Steven R. Weisman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/04/20/magazine/the-rajiv-generation.html |title=THE RAJIV GENERATION - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1986-04-20 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Gandhi's reliance on Doon alumni for political advice later led Prime Minister [[Morarji Desai]] to remark, \"If I had anything to do with this place, I'd close it down\".<ref name=\"bumiller1985\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/1987/0724/eindia.html|title=Bootstrap steps for Gandhi|date=24 July 1987|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref> Although any alumnus seldom held public office for some time afterward, this changed with the political ascendance of Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia, Naveen Patnaik, and Rahul Gandhi.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707070626/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2004-05-10/news/27376553_1_doon-school-naveen-patnaik-rahul-gandhi |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 July 2012 |title=Naveen Patnaik sets stage for GeNext Doscos |newspaper=The Times of India |date=10 May 2004 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Recent years: 2000\u2013present===\n[[Kanti Bajpai]] was the third old boy, after Gulab Ramchandani and Shomie Das, to become headmaste, when appointed to the post in 2003. He introduced numerous punishments, notably \"yellow cards\", to control an outburst of bullying at Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03cgg70 |title=BBC World Service - Path to Power, Educating India's Elite |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1994-10-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> In 2006, Bajpai found himself embroiled in a controversy when the parents of Hindu and Sikh students complained on discovering that the school's dining hall only serves [[halal]] meat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Bad-blood-over-meat-served-at-Doon-School/articleshow/1516879.cms|title=Bad blood over meat served at Doon School &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The fact came to light after a visiting Pakistani delegation was assured of their meal's halal status. Despite mounting pressure, the school's board of governors appealed for maintaining the status quo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/doon-debates-meaty-matters/story-mQ4y1Lt1fXLI3DiW2cV3XI.html|title=Doon debates meaty matters|date=3 May 2006|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> As of 2016, the school was serving both halal and non-halal (''[[jhatka]]'') meat varieties in the dining hall.<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2434-FINAL.pdf</ref> In 2009, [[Peter McLaughlin]], an Irish academic, was chosen to lead the school, becoming the first non-Indian headmaster in almost four decades.\n\n====2010 Founder's Day celebrations and film controversy====\n[[File:President of India speaking at The Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[President of India|President]] [[Pratibha Patil]] speaking at the school's 75th Founder's Day in October 2010.]]\n\nFounder's Day is a three-four day event in the autumn term, usually October, that marks the school's founding and draws many ex-pupils from all parts of the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/columnists/item/40943-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref> The chief guest is usually a prominent person.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/education/how-indias-renowned-doon-school-is-embracing-change-to-retain-its-exclusivity/articleshow/45006985.cms?from=mdr |title=How India's renowned Doon School is embracing change to retain its exclusivity - The Economic Times |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |date=2014-11-02 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The events include exhibitions, productions of plays, yoga sessions, live bands, a fete and an orchestral concert given by members of the school's Music Society.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Hill Post|url=http://hillpost.in/2011/10/28/doon-school-celebrates-76-th-founders-day/33352/latest-news/bhatt |title=Doon School celebrates 76 th founders day |date=28 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Datta |first=Sravasti |url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523113538/http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article1492611.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 May 2011 |title=Life & Style / Metroplus : All boarders on board |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=28 February 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon celebrated its 75th Founder's Day in 2010 and programmed events on an unprecedented scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/doon-school-to-celebrate-its-75th-anniversary-from-oct-21/articleshow/6712783.cms?from=mdr|title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21|date=8 October 2010|via=The Economic Times}}</ref><ref name=\"hindustantimes.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india/boys-will-be-boys/story-UxdKhDLhEGUVHIwaXe2e7H.html|title=Boys will be boys |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The event was christened ''DS-75''.<ref name=\"Doon school\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-08/news/27591639_1_celebrations-doon-school-chief-guest |title=Doon School to celebrate its 75th anniversary from Oct 21 |publisher=[[The Times Group]] |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School\">{{cite news|title=Founder's Day celebrations to begin at Doon School |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/15930-founders-day-celebrations-to-begin-at-doon-school.html |newspaper=Daily Pioneer|date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Among the chief guests were the then President [[Pratibha Patil]] of India, King [[Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck]] of Bhutan and [[Kapil Sibal]], (then [[Ministry of Human Resource Development (India)|Union Minister for Human Resource Development]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bhutanjournals.com/monarchy/hms-address-at-doon-school-dehradun-india/ |title=HM's Address at Doon School, Dehradun, India|newspaper=Bhutan Journals |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Pratibha Patil, in her address, urged the school authorities to make Doon a co-educational institution.<ref name=\"telegraphindia1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1101025/jsp/frontpage/story_13097199.jsp |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|title=Dame dilemma for Doon&nbsp;\u2013 President's co-ed suggestion evokes mixed reaction |date=25 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> One of the main events was a discussion, dubbed the \"Chandbagh Debate\", held between alumni including [[Vikram Seth]], [[Kamal Nath]], [[Manpreet Singh Badal]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]] and retired headmaster Kanti Bajpai, on the topic ''Can India lead?''. It was moderated by television commentator [[Karan Thapar]], an alumnus of the school.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/A+matter+of+debate+at+Doon+School+platinum+jubilee.-a0240443417 |title=A matter of debate at Doon School platinum jubilee|newspaper=[[India Today]] |date=23 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Ashvin Kumar]], an alumnus and Oscar-nominated director, made the film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'' for the celebrations, using pupils for the cast and crew. Most of it was shot in June and July during the summer break, and those scenes which required the entire student body were filmed after the school reopened in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imaginox.co.uk/course/1718 |title=Making 'Dazed in Doon' |publisher=Imaginox |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> It was screened on the final day of celebrations to a gathering of over 2000 people, including guests, students, parents and alumni.<ref name=dazed>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-14/news-interviews/28271042_1_film-doon-school-ashvin-kumar|title=Doon School bans Ashvin Kumar's film|newspaper=The Times of India|date=14 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> The day after screening, the school objected to the film and its distribution, obtaining a court order to delay its release and labelling it \"defamatory\".<ref name=fallout>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-18/news-interviews/28230561_1_doon-short-film-ashvin|title=Doon film fallout!|newspaper=The Times of India|date=18 November 2010|accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> The DVD sales on campus were immediately halted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Doon-School-bans-Ashvin-Kumars-film/articleshow/6919672.cms|title=Doon School bans Ashvin Kumar's film - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref name=ex-student-film>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-25/india/28269703_1_doon-school-ashvin-kumar-cbfc|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120701125916/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-25/india/28269703_1_doon-school-ashvin-kumar-cbfc|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 July 2012|title=Ex-student's film celebrating Doon draws school's ire|newspaper=The Times of India|date=25 December 2010}}</ref> The dispute  remains unresolved between the director and school authorities. On 22 October 2010, a commemorative postage stamp depicting the school's main building was released by the [[Indian Postal Service]] to mark the occasion of the 75th Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101009/dplus.htm#5 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=The Tribune |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Present day====\nIn June 2016, the school announced the appointment of Matthew Raggett, principal of the [[Leipzig International School]]'s secondary department, to succeed Peter McLaughlin as headmaster. Until the start of McLaughlin's headmastership, the student demographic was dominated by boys hailing from the [[North Indian]] states. To make the school more diverse, Raggett continued McLaughlin's outreach initiative of inviting more applications from boys in [[South Indian|South]] and [[Northeast India|Northeast Indian]] states.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/doon-school-looks-for-more-boys-from-south/articleshow/57725021.cms|title=Doon School: Doon School looks for more boys from south &#124; Bengaluru News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/doons-bonds-with-hyderabad/article7072329.ece|title=Doon\u2019s bonds with Hyderabad|first=R. Ravikanth|last=Reddy|date=6 April 2015|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> He also introduced a group discussion as part of the admissions process to test for critical thinking and peer interaction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/dehradun/after-8-decades-doon-school-looks-to-south-east-for-students/story-4uYQRMF8qalW61HFHuB0xM.html|title=After 8 decades, Doon School looks to South, East for students|date=3 July 2017|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> In January 2020, Matthew Raggett stepped down as the tenth headmaster citing personal reasons. In March 2020, the school was shut down and boys were sent home due to the [[COVID-19 outbreak]] and the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|Indian lockdown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/three-city-based-boarding-schools-close/articleshow/74662334.cms|title=Coronavirus scare: Three city-based boarding schools close &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Online classes are being conducted for students through video conferencing apps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-launch-online-classes-to-complete-syllabus/articleshow/74781758.cms|title=Schools launch online classes to complete syllabus in parts of Uttarakhand &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:FC Barcelona camp at Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|Main Field of the school with Kashmir and Hyderabad houses in the background.]]\n\nThe school is spread across a single campus covering approximately {{convert|72|acre|m2}} flanked by Chakrata Road and Mall Road in the [[Dehradun Cantonment]] area of Dehradun city, [[Uttarakhand]], India.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB114929995090170584 |title=The Andover of India? |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |first=Anita|last=Raghavan|date=24 June 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To house the school, the IPSS acquired Chandbagh Estate in Dehradun from the [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]] (FRI). Part of the estate was once a deer park. The IPSS also acquired an adjoining estate, now known as Skinner's Field, from the descendants of [[James Skinner (East India Company officer)|James Skinner]]. \n\n===Architecture===\nThe construction of the Main Building, then in FRI, was carried out by Imperial Public Works Department, and finished in 1911. Its Renaissance-style architecture was inspired by [[Basilica Palladiana]] in [[Vicenza]], Italy.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\" /> Many buildings on the campus have been designed by notable Indian architects or firms.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\" /> The library was designed by Romi Khosla, the Biology block by Ram Sharma, teachers' residences by Anagram Architects, and the new Arts and Media Centre, which was inaugurated in October 2010 and shortlisted for the 2010 World Architecture News Education Award, by alumnus Sandeep Khosla <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/5-schools-india-teach-lesson-design-architecture-pune-mumbai/|title=5 schools in India that offer a quick course in sensitive design and architecture|date=10 January 2020|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sandeep Khosla, Principal Architect , Khosla Associates |url=https://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/article/1507033/making-cut |title=Making the cut |publisher=Worldarchitecturenews.com |date=2011-02-13 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The Arts and Media Centre houses painting, ceramic, sculpture, and textile studios, along with a lecture hall, film and photography studio, publications' room and exhibition galleries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/86476/arts-and-media-centre-at-the-doon-school-khosla-associates/|title=Arts and Media Centre at the Doon School / Khosla Associates|date=4 November 2010|website=ArchDaily}}</ref> In 2016, the school's Main Building received an \"Honourable Mention\" under the [[UNESCO Asia Pacific Heritage Awards|UNESCO Asia-Pacific Awards for Cultural Heritage Conservation]], following the conservation work carried out by Aishwarya Tipnis Architects on the more than a century-old building.<ref name=\"Architectural Digest, Doon campus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/doon-school-campus-extension-anagram-architects/|title=Take a tour of India\u2019s most elite private school, The Doon School campus|date=21 March 2018|website=Architectural Digest India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.one.un.org/page/restoration-of-prayer-hall-at-japan-shrine-wins-top-honor-in-unesco-asia-pacific-heritage-awards/ |title=Restoration of prayer hall at Japan shrine wins top honor in UNESCO Asia- Pacific Heritage Awards - UN India |publisher=In.one.un.org |date=2016-09-01 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Natural environment===\nThe school estate, known as Chandbagh, lies in the green zone of the city and occupies the former site of the Imperial Forest Research Institute, now [[Forest Research Institute (India)|Forest Research Institute]]. A wide variety of [[flora]] and [[fauna]] are found on campus, including many rare trees that date back to the days of the FRI.<ref name=\"Fountain Ink essay\">{{cite web|url=https://fountainink.in/essay/no-common-or-garden-affair |title=No common or garden affair &#124; Fountain Ink |publisher=Fountainink.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj\" /> The school has over 150 species of trees on its campus, and the formal gardens attract a variety of birds.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Prashant |first=Shishir |url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/doon-schools-etp-may-be-trendsetter/428364/ |title=Doon school's ETP may be trendsetter |newspaper=[[Business Standard]] |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 1996, a book titled ''Trees of Chandbagh'' was released which provided a comprehensive account of vegetation found on Doon's campus.<ref name=\"TreesofChandbagh\">{{cite book|last=Sahni|first=K. C.|title=Trees of Chandbagh: Doon's national heritage|year=1996|publisher=Konark Publishers|location=Delhi|isbn=978-81-220-0457-1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> Along similar lines, the illustrated book ''Birds of Chandbagh: A Guide To Birding at The Doon School'' was released in 2019, featuring photographs, illustrations and [[QR codes]] documenting the [[bird calls]] of the species found on campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.in/BIRDS-CHANDBAGH-guide-birding-School/dp/B084HG4R87 |title=Buy BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Book Online at Low Prices in India &#124; BIRDS of CHANDBAGH- A guide to birding at The Doon School Reviews & Ratings |publisher=Amazon.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> The school has devised an Architectural and Projects Committee, which ensures that any construction taking place on campus is done without disturbing the ecological balance of the wooded school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/7-days/studies-in-style/cid/598008 |title=Studies in style |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2017-10-30 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===Houses===\n[[File:TataHouseQuadinDoon.jpg|thumb|right|East wing of Tata House and the quad.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:80%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | House name and Colours\n|-\n! House\n! Colour\n! Swatch\n|-\n|Kashmir || Yellow || {{colour box|#fecb00}}\n|-\n|Oberoi || Sky blue || {{colour box|#00add0}}\n|-\n|Tata || Red || {{colour box|#c60c30}}\n|-\n|Jaipur || Green || {{colour box|#007934}}\n|-\n|Hyderabad || Navy Blue || {{colour box|#003359}}\n|-\n|Martyn || || {{colour box|#496c60}}\n|-\n|Foot || ||{{colour box|#589199}}\n|}\n\nDoon follows the [[house system]]; there are five main houses (Hyderabad, Jaipur, Kashmir, Tata and Oberoi) and two 'holding houses' (Foot and Martyn, named after former headmasters), for boys in their first year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/pastoral-care/boarding-at-doon/|title=Boarding at Doon|website=Doon School}}</ref> The original four houses (Oberoi was added in 1991) were named after the largest initial donors: Hyderabad House was named after [[Akbar Hydari]], who secured a contribution from [[Nizam of Hyderabad]]'s government; Kashmir House, after [[Maharajah]] [[Hari Singh]], then ruler of [[Jammu and Kashmir]]; Tata House, after the [[Tata family|Tata]] Trusts; and Jaipur House, after [[Rai Bahadur]] Amarnath Atal arranged for contributions from the [[Durbar (court)|Durbar]] of [[Jaipur]].<ref>Sanjay Srivastava, ''Constructing post-colonial India: national character and the Doon School (London: Routledge, 1998), p. 197 (Appendix 1): \"Donors to the Indian Public Schools' Society prior to 1936\"</ref> \n\nBoys are assigned to houses at the time of admission and develop great loyalty to them, since all [[intramural sports]] involve fierce competition between houses. Each house is run by a housemaster or a housemistress, along with a house captain and a team of [[School prefect|prefects]]. One senior boy serves as [[school captain]], chosen by teachers and students voting in a [[secret ballot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ludhiana/Ludhiana-lad-is-Doon-School-captain/articleshow/18424444.cms |title=Ludhiana lad is Doon School captain &#124; Ludhiana News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2013-02-10 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref>  The housemistress is assisted by a [[matron]] known as \"The Dame\", who provides [[pastoral care]] for pupils, some of whom take several weeks to adjust fully to life in a boarding school, particularly given Doon's monastic lifestyle and strict routine.<ref name=\"outlookindia2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?230938 |title=Class Up At Doon &#124; Anjali Puri |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Futehally\"> {{cite book |last1=Futehally |first1=Laeeq |title=The Last Englishman: The Life and Times of Jack Gibson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3iw1CgAAQBAJ&dq=the+last+englishman+jack+gibson&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2015 |publisher=Hachette UK |location=London |language= |isbn=9789350099698 |page= |chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= The food and linen was the responsibility of the Dame (Matron)}}</ref> The homes of housemasters and housemistresses are adjacent or physically attached to their houses to enable close supervision and support.\n\n==Academics==\n[[File:The Doon School.jpg|thumb|250px|Main Building of the school which houses classrooms and offices.]]\nThe school practices a five-and-a-half-day week consisting of 40 periods (or \"schools\"), each of 40 minutes. The school day begins with \"first bell\" soon after 6:15&nbsp;am. The boys have [[chhota haazri]] before doing [[calisthenics]] outdoors on the playing fields, which is then followed by classes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2004-07-04/special-report/27149351_1_education-system-elite-schools-vikram-seth |title=Chhota Hazri bell tolls for desi Etons|newspaper=The Times of India |date=4 July 2004 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The student-teacher ratio at the school is 10:1.<ref name=\"excellence\">{{cite journal|title=Excellence personified |journal=Frontline |date=12 February 2011 |volume=28 |issue=4 |url=http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110313163529/http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2804/stories/20110225280412800.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 March 2011 |accessdate=2 March 2012 }}</ref> Doon pupils take the [[International General Certificate of Secondary Education]] (IGCSE) exams in [[tenth grade]], which replaced [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education]] in 2017, and are thereafter offered two strands for the final two years: [[International Baccalaureate]] (IB) or [[Indian School Certificate]] (ISC).<ref name=\"autogenerated2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ibo.org/en/school/002603 |title=The Doon School - International Baccalaureate\u00ae |publisher=Ibo.org |date=2006-08-28 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe academic year has three terms: spring, summer and autumn. New pupils (\"D-Formers or 7th Graders\") join Doon at the beginning of April.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kapoor |first=Jaskiran |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/class-apart/601507/0 |title=Class Apart |publisher=Indian Express |date=11 April 2010 |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref> The autumn term runs from August to the year-end examinations in November after which the boys are promoted to the new class beginning in February. These internal examinations are known as \"trials\", while examinations leading to certificates such as the [[Indian School Certificate]] are known as \"finals\". Discipline at the school has always been strict, and the school has expelled children from well-known families. In the 1950s, Martyn's suggestion that [[Sanjay Gandhi]] finish his senior year elsewhere was accepted without question by his mother, Indira Gandhi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2008/20081202/dplus1.htm |title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India&nbsp;\u2014 Dehradun Plus |work=The Tribune |accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> \n\nSocial work, known formally as \"Socially Useful Productive Work\", is also part of school life. All boys of the school must complete a mandatory quota of social service hours every term.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/141122/nation-education/article/doon-school-scouts-tamil-nadu-students |title=Doon School scouts for Tamil Nadu students |publisher=Deccanchronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Doon also oversees a Panchayat Ghar teaching impoverished children, and many building projects and workshops for the local community. Pupils and alumni have frequently helped local villages of organised efforts across India to assist people affected by natural disasters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roundsquare.org/educational-insights/the-doon-school-a-village-service-partnership/ |title=The Doon School: A Village Service Partnership |publisher=Round Square |date=2019-02-19 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> During the [[1991 Uttarkashi earthquake]] the school's amateur radio club was used by the government for communication purposes.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gautam|first=Ashutosh|title=Earthquake: A Natural Disaster|year=2008|publisher=APH Publishing|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-313-0337-5|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oSbTJDwMFgAC&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=doon+school+uttarkashi+earthquake#v=onepage&q=doon%20school%20uttarkashi%20earthquake&f=false}}</ref>  \n\n===Traditions===\nThe early headmasters and teachers at Doon came from traditional British public schools, and the jargon introduced by them is still in use. For example, the weekly masters' meeting, started by Foot, is called ''Chambers'', a term taken from Eton, and evening \"prep\" (the boarding-school equivalent of homework) is called ''toye-time'', a term taken from [[Winchester College]].<ref>{{cite book|first1=Charles |last1=Stevens|first2=Christopher|last2=Stray|title=Winchester notions: the English dialect of Winchester College|publisher=Athlone Press|year=1998|page=294|quote=Toy-time, or toytime recorded from 1831 as the evening hours of preparation, called 'prep' elsewhere&nbsp;...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB917469665815143000 |title=Language Lessons: For India's Elite English Is the Past -- and the Future\n|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date= |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The school songs were deliberately chosen to include both [[Urdu poetry]] and Hindu [[bhajan]]s as a way of emphasising Doon's secular ethos; similarly, the school prayers include a mix of Anglican hymns and Indian poetry.<ref>The Doon School Prayer book p.02-26</ref> Attendance at the morning assembly is required of all pupils and teachers. It traditionally begins with a song from the school's Song Book, which includes: ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]], ''Chisti Ne Jis Zamin Mein'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''Anand Loke'' by [[Rabindranath Tagore]]; ''[[Saare Jahan Se Achcha]]'' by [[Muhammad Iqbal]]; ''[[Lab Pe Aati Hai Dua]]'' by Muhammad Iqbal; ''Vandana Ke in Swaron Mein'' (a [[Bhajan|bhajan]]); ''Ghungat Ke Pat Khol Re'' (attributed to [[Meerabai]]); ''Pitu Matu Sahayak'' (a bhajan); ''[[Vande Mataram]]'' (from a poem by [[Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay]]). Although ''[[Jana Gana Mana]]'' is India's [[National anthem]], it is traditionally referred to as \"Song No. 1\" at Doon since it was adopted as the School Song in 1935, fifteen years before it was adopted as India's national anthem.<ref>Bathla, Sanjeev<''Chotta Hazri:A Dosco's yatra'' p.32</ref><ref name=\"srivastava\">{{cite book|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School (p.82)|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WAdkjptj7zwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School&cd=2#v=onepage&q=song&f=false|isbn=9780415178563|year=1998}}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular activities==\n{{Anchor|Athletics}}\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Cricket at Doon.jpg|thumb|left|A cricket game in progress on the Main Field.]]\n\nSports are compulsory for pupils. The school has over {{convert|30|acre|m2}} of playing fields, the largest of which are Skinner's Field and the Main Field. Cricket and hockey dominate the sports calendar in spring term, while football, athletics and boxing are played in autumn term. Other sports such as tennis, table tennis, badminton, squash, basketball, swimming and gymnastics are played all-year round. Inter-house matches are played in cricket, hockey, football and basketball. Sports facilities include a 25-metre swimming pool, a boxing ring and a multi-purpose hall with a gymnasium, yoga studio, and facilities for indoor badminton, basketball and table tennis. There are two [[artificial turf]] cricket pitches, five basketball courts, four tennis courts, four squash courts, eight cricket nets, seven fields for hockey and football (which can be converted to four cricket pitches to accommodate seasonal sports), a modern cricket pavilion and two 400-metre athletics tracks. In 2014, the school inaugurated a shooting range on campus. Golf is offered to boys in partnership with local golf courses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/academic-life/departments/sports/|title=Sports|website=Doon School}}</ref> Doon hosts the annual Afzal Khan Memorial Basketball Tournament, an inter-school tournament that draws all major school basketball teams of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/features/the-asian-school-bag-bball-trophy-233461 |title=The Asian School bag b\u2019ball trophy |publisher=The Tribune India |date=2016-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/inside-the-hoop-dreams-of-21-boys-at-nbas-first-academy-in-india/articleshow/58979953.cms?from=mdr |title=NBA: Inside the hoop dreams of 21 boys at NBA\u2019s first academy in India - The Economic Times |date=2017-06-04 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020504/ncr3.htm |title=Tribune Online Edition, May 4, 2002 |work=The Tribune |date=4 May 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys visit other schools and academies from time to time to take part in various tournaments. For skill improvement, the school often invites professional sports bodies to hold training camps, which are usually open to students from across India. In 2013, a football coaching camp was held in association with Bar\u00e7a Academy, the official training school of [[FC Barcelona]],<ref>https://www.doonschool.com/f-c-barcelona-at-doon-july-2013/</ref> and in January 2015, coaches from the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] held a week-long cricket training camp on the school grounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pitchvision.com/exclusive-inside-mcc-lords-club-india-coaching-camp-drills |title=Live Local Matches &#124; Tips & Techniques &#124; Articles & Podcasts |publisher=PitchVision |date=2017-07-24 |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>http://educationworld.co/Magazines/EWIssueSection.aspx?Issue=September_2015&Section=Boarding_Schools&Article=India%27s_best_boys_boarding_school</ref>\n\n===Clubs and societies===\n{{See|The Doon School Model United Nations}}\n[[File:The Doon School Weekly.jpg|thumb|''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication of Doon. It is produced by the boys and distributed every Saturday morning.]]\n\nExtracurricular activities are also a compulsory element of school life.  There are around 70-80 clubs and societies, including astronomy, business, [[The Doon School Model United Nations]], quiz, photography and film, [[Model aircraft|aeromodelling]], robotics, paper recycling, weather reporting, pottery, carpentry, [[amateur radio]] and birdwatching, among others.<ref>{{cite web|author=\" + arr[2] + \" |url=https://www.outlookbusiness.com/cest-la-vie/the-good-life/a-class-act-5412 |title=Premium schools |publisher=Outlook Business |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> In many societies pupils come together to discuss a particular topic, presided over by a schoolmaster and often including a guest speaker. The school has often invited prominent figures to give speeches and talks to the students; these have included heads of state, politicians, ornithologists, naturalists, artists, writers, economists, diplomats and industrialists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/category/events/visiting-speakers/|title=Visiting Speakers Archives|website=Doon School}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/600-mn-to-be-enrolled-in-uidai-in-next-4-years-nilekani/714784 |title=600 Mn to be Enrolled in UIDAI in Next 4 Years: Nilekani |publisher=Outlookindia.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nBoys can write for, or join the editorial board of, a number of school magazines that are published in English or Hindi. ''[[The Doon School Weekly]]'', established in 1936, is the oldest publication and the official school newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/34/42/obituary/ |title=OBITUARY : Himalayan Journal vol.34/42 |publisher=Himalayanclub.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref> Distributed every Saturday morning, and edited by pupils, it chronicles school activities and is a platform for creative, political or humorous writing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=1 March 2012}}</ref> The publication aims to represent the views of the school community as well as Old Boys, and include satire and criticism of school policies. More subversive publications, critical of teachers and the school establishment, have occasionally been produced without official sponsorship. Other magazines include ''The Yearbook'', a heavily illustrated publication for recording all highlights of the school year, and ''The Doon School Information Review'' for cultural criticism. Specialist publications by academic departments include '' Vibgyor'' (Art), ''Echo'' (Science), ''The Econocrat'' (Economics), ''Infinity'' (Mathematics), ''Grand Slam'' (Sports) and ''The Circle'' (History and Political Science).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/clubs-societies/publications/|title=Publications|website=Doon School}}</ref>\n\n===Mountaineering===\n{{Main|Role of The Doon School in Indian mountaineering}}\n\n[[File:Mt. Everest Base Camp Expedition - 2008, The Doon School.jpg|thumb|left|2008 expedition to the [[Mount Everest Base Camp]] and [[Kala Patthar]].]]\n\nHalfway through each term, the boys go on a one-week \"midterm\", an expedition through the [[Siwalik Hills]] or [[Himalayas]]. Senior boys make treks of up to five days, unaccompanied by teachers, camping out in tents and cooking their own food. The trips are planned by students themselves. Alumni have recalled these midterms as being among their most formative and character-building experiences.<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/how-the-playing-fields-of-doon-nurture-india-incs-best-leaders/articleshow/6872417.cms|title=How the playing fields of Doon nurture India Inc's best leaders |newspaper=The Times of India |date=5 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Doon has been credited with pioneering mountaineering in India, due to the accomplishments of masters such as [[R.L. Holdsworth]], [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]], and alumni like [[Narendra Dhar Jayal|Nandu Jayal]], who later became the founder principal of [[Himalayan Mountaineering Institute]].<ref name=\"Kohli\"> {{cite book |last1=Kohli |first1=M.S. |title=Mountains of India: Tourism, Adventure and Pilgrimage |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Mountains_of_India.html?id=GIs4zv17HHwC&redir_esc=y |date=2002 |publisher=Indus |location= |language= |isbn=9788173871351 |pages= |chapter= |chapterurl= |page=209 |quote= p.290, Much of the credit for early interest in mountaineering among Indians goes to the Doon School, largely because of some distinguished British mountaineers on its staff like J.A.K. Martyn, J.T.M. Gibson, R.L. Holdsworth...In 1951, Gurdial Singh of the Doon School climbed the 7,120 metres high Trisul. This was the first Indian summit.}}</ref> Notable climbs by staff and alumni include [[Bandarpunch]] (6,316&nbsp;m) in 1950, Kala Nag (6,387&nbsp;m) in 1956, [[Trisul]] (7,120&nbsp;m) in 1951, [[Kamet]] (7,756&nbsp;m) in 1955, [[Abi Gamin]] (7,355&nbsp;m) in 1953 and 1955, Mrigthuni (6,855&nbsp;m) in 1958 and Jaonli (6,632 metres) in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.himalayanclub.org/hj/62/16/early-years-of-indian-mountaineering/ |title=Early Years of Indian Mountaineering |publisher=Himalayan Club |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> Some of these expeditions have been noted for their idiosyncrasies. After Gurdial Singh led a successful climb of Trisul, he performed a headstand [[asana]] on the summit as a tribute to the Hindu god [[Shiva]], who is said to abide there. Holdsworth smoked a pipe on reaching the summit of [[Kamet]] (7.756m), its first ascent, in 1931.<ref name=\"Harish Kapadia\"> {{cite book |last1=Kapadia |first1=Harish |title=Across Peaks and Passes in Garhwal Himalaya |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Across_Peaks_Passes_in_Garhwal_Himalaya.html?id=KptmxrqhKl4C |date=1999 |publisher=Indus Publishing |location=London |language=English |isbn=9788173870972 |page=17 |quote=The peak of Kamet was attempted several times and finally in 1931 Frank Smythe and Eric Shipton reached the summit along with some others. R.L. Holdsworth, who was with them, smoked a pipe on the summit, which I believe still remains a height record for smokers.}}</ref> Two Doon pupils climbed the [[Matterhorn]] in 1951 wearing cricket boots.<ref name=\"alpinejournal\">{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Richard|title=Climbing with the Doon School|journal=Alpine Journal|year=2001|pages=197\u2013201|url=http://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_2001_files/AJ%202001%20197-201%20Anderson%20Doon%20School.pdf|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre and music===\n[[File:Waiting for Godot in Doon School.jpg|thumb|[[Samuel Beckett]]'s ''[[Waiting for Godot]]'' being staged in the Rose Bowl.]]\nAn [[amphitheatre]] known as the Rose Bowl was built largely by pupils in two years during the 1930s<ref name=\"wsj\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Martyn|first=Mady|title=Martyn Sahib, the Story of John Martyn of the Doon School|year=1985|publisher=|location=Delhi|isbn=|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Martyn_Sahib_the_story_of_John_Martyn_of.html?id=CdU2AAAAIAAJ|page=130|quote=It took two years to complete the open air theatre. The first play staged on it was \"The Merchant of Venice prodcued by Jack Gibson, and he had all his actors dressed in Indian costumes.\"}}</ref> and underwent a major structural change in 2009.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Santayana|first=Vivek|title=Losing a Kidney|journal=The Doon School Weekly|date=24 October 2009|issue=2232|url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|accessdate=27 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66UfGMuG8?url=http://www.doonschool.com/images/weekly_pdf/2232.pdf|archivedate=28 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It can seat up to 2,000 people and has been the setting for numerous [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] plays and other classics of western theatre, as well as musical performances and speeches during school ceremonies such as Founder's Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120805061511/http://www.mtholyoke.edu/~ptyagi/Doon%20Online%20-%20Vikram%20Seth.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 August 2012 |title=Doon Online&nbsp;\u2013 Vikram Seth |publisher=Mtholyoke.edu |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The Multi-Purpose Hall is a more modern indoor theatre that can accommodate approximately 2,000 people. Plays are regularly staged in [[English language|English]] and [[Hindi]], with 8\u20139 productions each year including 2 major productions as part of the Founder's Day celebrations. The Inter House Once-Act Play competition is held each year, alternatively in English and Hindi. Many of the plays historically have been joint productions with the Welham Girls' School in [[Dehradun]].\n\nIn 2001 a new music school was built beside the Rose Bowl. It houses a [[music library]], a [[concert hall]] and several practice and teaching rooms where students learn various western and Indian instruments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doonschool.com/co-curricular/stas-and-activities/music/|title=Music Programme and Facilities at The Doon School|website=Doon School}}</ref> Pupils of the school have an option to appear for the [[Trinity Guildhall]] music examinations, conducted by [[Trinity College London]], in [[piano]], [[violin]], drums and classical guitar. In 2002 the school choir raised {{Indian Rupee}}2&nbsp;million for victims of the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake]] by organising a charity concert with the title ''Concerto 2000'', in which drummer [[Sivamani]] also took part.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mp/2002/04/11/stories/2002041100070300.htm |title=Raga meets rhythm |newspaper=The Hindu |date=11 April 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/lf/2002/03/30/stories/2002033000930200.htm |title=Doon tunes |newspaper=The Hindu |date=30 March 2002 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> To commemorate its Platinum Jubilee, the school launched a music album called ''Spirit of Doon'' in collaboration with [[EMI]].<ref name=\"bare_url\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-14/news-and-interviews/28261521_1_music-album-doscos-alumni |title=Doon goes musical|newspaper=The Times of India |date=14 November 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The school choir sang two songs (\"Lab pe Aati Hai Dua\" and \"Anand Loke\") for the project but only the former was included in the final recording. The tracks were written by the lyricist [[Gulzar]] and were sung by [[Sonu Nigam]], Shayan Italia and [[Bhajan Sopori]].<ref name=\"bare_url\" />\n\n==Affiliations==\n\n===Ties with other schools===\n\nFrom its foundation in 1937 until the early 1980s, [[Welham Boys' School]] was a [[feeder school]] for Doon School and Mayo College.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/dehradun/31886-welham-boys-school-to-celebrate-platinum-jubilee-year.html |title=Welham Boys' School to celebrate platinum jubilee year |newspaper=Daily Pioneer |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> This ended when Surendra Kandhari, an old boy and former housemaster at Doon, became Principal of Welham and transformed it into a high school. Several families who send their sons to Doon send their daughters to [[Welham Girls' School]], and many Doon alumni have married alumnae of Welham.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070121/ttlife1.htm |title=The Tribune Lifestyle |newspaper=The Tribune |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The two schools hold an annual \"dance social\", and their alumni sometimes collaborate in organising events. Pakistani ex-pupils from Doon established the [[Chand Bagh School]] 40&nbsp;km north of [[Lahore]], Pakistan, in 1998, modelling it on the general structure of Doon.<ref>{{cite web|author=Azhar M. A. Qureshi |url=http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611010826/http://www.chandbagh.edu.pk/cbs/handba.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 June 2009 |title=Chand Bagh School |publisher=Chandbagh.edu.pk |accessdate=24 January 2012 }}</ref> Doon also has exchange programmes with a number of overseas schools, such as Eton College, Harrow School, [[St. Albans School (Washington, D.C.)|St. Albans School, Washington DC]], [[Millfield]], [[Schule Schloss Salem]], [[The Armidale School]], [[Bridge House School]], [[Deerfield Academy]], [[King's Academy]], [[Stowe School]], [[Scotch College, Melbourne]], [[The Hutchins School]] and [[St. Mark's School (Texas)]]. In 2011 Doon twinned with [[The Thomas Hardye School]], Dorchester, [[England]], through a cultural exchange project organised by the [[BBC]] and [[British Council]] in light of the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] held in the [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9451296.stm|title=Schools Spotlight on Team Abhinav Bindra|publisher=BBC|date=8 April 2011|accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Schools with similar names===\nAs private schools became more widespread in [[India]], several other schools used \"Doon\" as part of their names, causing some confusion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/schools-using-doon-in-their-names-to-cash-the-popularity-of-the-doon-school/articleshow/69224014.cms |title=Schools using Doon in their names to cash the popularity of The Doon School &#124; Dehradun News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-05-08 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> Among them are Doon Global School, Doon Presidency School, [[Doon International School (Palia Kalan)|Doon International School]], Doon Preparatory School, Doon Cambridge School, Doon Girls School, [[Doon Public School]] (in West Delhi, not the Doon Valley) and the Doon College of Spoken English. None of them are related to The Doon School.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-10-24/special-report/28263544_1_doon-school-ipsc-sainik-schools |title=Is the old school tie wearing thin?|newspaper=The Times of India |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Memberships===\nThe Doon School is a member of following organisations: [[G20 Schools]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Gold |first=Adam |url=http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028073515/http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 October 2007 |title=Move over G8\u2014this is G20 > Harvard Westlake Chronicle Online |publisher=Students.hw.com |date=8 November 2006 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Round Square]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925000935/http://www.roundsquare.org/index.php?id=67 |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 September 2012 |title=Doon School India |publisher=RoundSquare |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Interact Club|Rotary International's Interact Club]], [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmc.org.uk/schools/the-doon-school/ |title=HMC Schools : International Members |publisher=Hmc.org.uk |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[International Boys' Schools Coalition]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theibsc.org/page.cfm?p=38&filter_data7=&filter_data10=INDIA&filter_data13=&filter_data15=&key=&submit=SEARCH |title=International Boys' Schools Coalition: Member Directory |publisher=Theibsc.org |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Council for the Indian School Certificate Examinations]], [[International Baccalaureate|International Baccalaureate Organization (IBO)]], Indian Public Schools' Conference,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120802223143/http://www.ipsc.co.in/IPSC_Pages/member_detail_popup.aspx?id=66 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 August 2012 |title=Indian Public Schools' Conference |publisher=Ipsc.co.in |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Rashtriya Life Saving Society (India)]], [[International Award Association]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Pioneer |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/doon-school-becomes-first-indian-school-to-start-iayp-online.html |title=Doon School becomes first Indian school to start IAYP online |publisher=Dailypioneer.com |date=2014-08-06 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe school is the regional test centre for [[University of Cambridge ESOL Examinations]] and [[SAT]] Tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ivyzone.com/category/sat/test-centre/ |title=SAT l STUDY ABROAD l VISA I IvyZone.com &#124; Test-centre |publisher=Ivyzone.com |date=22 March 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public image==\n;Doon in films & television\n{{main|Dazed in Doon}}\n{{main|Indian Summer School}}\n\n* The film ''[[Dazed in Doon]]'', which was commissioned by the School on the occasion of its 75th anniversary and produced by old boy Ashvin Kumar, was banned by the school authorities because it \"doesn't give the school a good name\". The dispute remains unresolved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-path-not-taken/article2924231.ece|title=The path not taken|first=Sudhish|last=Kamath|date=23 February 2012|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref>\n* In September 2010, [[BBC Sport]] made a documentary on the Doon School for the ''World Olympic Dreams'' Project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/9075650.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 The school that breeds Indian medal winners |publisher=BBC News |date=11 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> The documentary was produced in association with the [[British Council]]. Its main purpose was to show the school where [[Abhinav Bindra]], the first Indian individual Olympic gold medallist, spent his formative years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;\u2013 Abhinav Bindra, India |publisher=BBC News |date=26 July 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n* In 2017, [[Channel 4]] of UK commissioned a 3-part documentary, ''[[Indian Summer School]]'', where working-class boys from the UK were given a chance to study at Doon for a term to see if they would benefit from the all-round experience of an Indian residential school. The filming began in August 2017, and the programmes were broadcast in March\u2013April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/mar/29/indian-summer-school-review-five-terrible-teens-are-sent-to-indias-equivalent-of-eton |title=Indian Summer School review \u2013 five terrible teens are sent to India\u2019s equivalent of Eton &#124; Television & radio |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n;Doon in literature\n* [[Vikram Seth]] used his own experiences of being bullied at Doon to model the character of Tapan in ''[[A Suitable Boy]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Huang |first1=Guiyou |title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Asian American Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/The_Greenwood_Encyclopedia_of_Asian_Amer.html?id=d5RxDwAAQBAJ |date=2009 |publisher=[[Greenwood Press]] |location=Westport, Connecticut |language= |isbn=9781567207361 |page=860 |quote=...as a boarder at the prestigious Doon School, known as \"the Eton of India\" on Dehradun. Whilst at school, Seth encountered abuse and bullying from many of his fellow classmates, an experience that he later evokes by the character Tapan, the youngest of the Chaterjees, in ''A Suitable Boy''.}}</ref>\n* In [[Salman Rushdie]]'s short-story anthology [[East, West]], the protagonists Zulu and Chekhov are Doscos.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Damrosch |first1=David |title=How to Read World Literature |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/How_to_Read_World_Literature.html?id=1VYsDwAAQBAJ |date=2017 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Son]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781119009245 |page=172 |quote=Chekhov and Zulu became ''Star Trek'' devotees while still in school in India...Significantly, they are enrolled in the Doon School, an elite British-style academy established in the waning years of British Raj.}}</ref>\n* In [[Tenzing Norgay]]'s autobiography ''Man of Everest'', he refers to [[Bandarpunch]] as \"The Doon School mountain\" due to the fact that the mountain was frequented by two Doon School teachers [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] and [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John Martyn]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Norgay |first1=Tenzing |title=Man of Everest \u2013 The Autobiography of Tenzing |url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=90IPAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=doon+school+mountain |date=1955 |publisher=[[George G. Harrap and Co.]] |location=London |language= |isbn=9781447400288 |page=154 |quote= It was to Garhwal. Back to Bandar Punch, \"the Doon School mountain,\" with my old friend Mr Gibson. }}</ref>\n* In [[Ruskin Bond]]'s novella ''Strangers in the Night'', character Jai Shankar is from Doon.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bond |first1=Ruskin |title=Strangers in the Night |url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Strangers_on_the_Roof.html?id=58nqMgEACAAJ |date=1994 |publisher=[[Penguin Books India]] |location= |language= |isbn=9780140240658 |page=4 |quote=William and Jai did not trail me to this place, as it was a little lowbrow for them (William being Swiss and Jai being Doon School.}}</ref>\n* [[Penguin Books|Penguin's]] ''The Great Speeches of Modern India'' (2011) included Vikram Seth's 1992 Founder's Day address, which being confessional surprised the school community, and [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]]'s 2007 speech, which was noted for its wit and humour.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z7dCH_IYbt8C&q=doon+school#v=snippet&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=The Great Speeches of Modern India - Rudranghsu Mukherjee - Google Books |date= October 2011|accessdate=16 July 2017|isbn=9788184002348 |last1=Mukherjee |first1=Rudranghsu }}</ref>\n\n;Doon in research\n* ''Doon School Chronicles'' is the first of five [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] films called the ''Doon School Quintet'', made by David MacDougall between 1997 and 2000 about the culture of the School.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://raifilm.org.uk/films/doon-school-chronicles/|title=Film : \u201cDoon School Chronicles\u201d \u2013 RAI Ethnographic Film Catalogue}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220001143/http://www.berkeleymedia.com/catalog/berkeleymedia/films/global_and_development_studies/doon_school_chronicles |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 February 2006 |title=Berkeley Media LLC: Catalog: Doon School Chronicles |publisher=Berkeleymedia.com |accessdate=20 February 2012 }}</ref> Macdougall has written of a tendency of some alumni to idealise a ''[[Golden age (metaphor)|Golden Age]]'' set in the first decade of the school's life, which sometimes makes them resistant to change.<ref name=\"MacDougall2006-p107-108\">{{citation|last=MacDougall|first=David|title=The corporeal image: film, ethnography, and the senses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&pg=PA107|accessdate=31 March 2012|year=2006|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-12156-7|pages=107\u2013108}}</ref><ref>{{cite video|first=David|last=MacDougall|url=http://www.roninfilms.com.au/feature/526/doon-school-chronicles.html |title=DOON SCHOOL CHRONICLES|publisher=Ronin Films|accessdate=20 February 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School'' by Sanjay Srivastva is a detailed [[Sociology|sociological]] study of the school's culture and how it has influenced India's national character.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School|title=Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School|first=Sanjay|last=Srivastva}}</ref>\n* ''{{'}}Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools'', a 2005 report by the Institute of Social Studies Trust, discusses why the Doon School has no [[Reservation in India|reservations]] (quotas for specific social groups) in its admissions process. The post quotes an unnamed student who explains, \"passing the Doon School entrance exam means that you have proved yourself worthy of the school. Reserving seats for students seems to imply that the school must prove itself worthy of you.\"<ref>{{cite web |author=Mallica |title='Poor' Children in 'Rich' Schools |url=http://www.isst-india.org/PDF/Poor%20children%20in%20Rich%20school.pdf |publisher=Institute of Social Studies Trust |accessdate=30 March 2012}}{{dead link|date=February 2017}}</ref>\n* In 1969, [[Asian Survey]] (then Asian Review) - an Asian studies [[academic journal]] of [[University of California, Berkeley]] - produced a report on The Doon School as a part of their project which documented Indian history after the entry of [[East India Company]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sh4sAQAAIAAJ&q=doon+school&dq=doon+school |title=Asian review&nbsp;\u2014 Demetrius Charles Boulger, East India Association (London, England), Oriental Institute (Woking, England)  |accessdate=30 March 2013|last1=Boulger |first1=Demetrius Charles |year=1969 }}</ref>\n* In ''Indian Tales of the Raj'', Zareer Masani studies how Doon School's alumni affected the Indian political scene in the '60s.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Lm4FVb54_oUC&pg=PA152&dq=doon+school#v=onepage&q=doon%20school&f=false |title=Indian Tales of the Raj&nbsp;\u2014 Zareer Masani  |accessdate=30 March 2013|isbn=9780520071278 |last1=Masani |first1=Zareer |year=1988 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n===Alumni===\n\n\n{{Main|List of The Doon School alumni}}\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School alumni}}\n[[File:Vikram Seth, in Oxfordshire.jpg|thumb|right|175px|[[Vikram Seth]] (Class of 1969), novelist and poet, author of ''[[A Suitable Boy]]'' and ''[[The Golden Gate]]''.]]\n\nPupils are known as \"Doscos\", a contraction of \"Doon\" and \"school\". The vast majority of alumni are Indians, but a dwindling number are from Pakistan having studied at Doon before the [[Partition of India]] forced them to leave in 1947. Relations between Indian and Pakistani alumni have remained warm over the years, despite the long history of conflict between the two countries.<ref name=\"tribuneindia.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20101024/dplus.htm#2 |title=Dehradun Plus |newspaper=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |date=24 October 2010 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Boys from Bangladesh and Nepal continue to study at Doon. Pupils of Doon have achieved prominence in politics, government service, the armed forces of India and Pakistan, commerce, journalism, the arts and literature.<ref name=\"suitablejoy\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/1999/mar/27/books.guardianreview1 |title=A suitable joy|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 March 1999 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes1993\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/02/magazine/vikram-seth-s-big-book.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |title=Vikram Seth's Big Book&nbsp;\u2013 New York Times |work=The New York Times |date=2 May 1993 |accessdate=27 March 2012}}</ref> They include [[Union Cabinet of India|cabinet ministers]], [[Chief minister (India)|chief ministers]], several members of the [[Parliament of India|Indian Parliament]] and [[Legislative Assembly|state Legislative Assemblies]], diplomats, and former heads of the Indian and Pakistani Air Forces.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/06/01/stories/2009060153270700.htm |title=Other States / Uttaranchal News : Seven Doon alumni in 15th Lok Sabha |newspaper=The Hindu |date=1 June 2009 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> Former Prime Minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]] was educated at Doon.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/13/magazine/mrs-gandhi-grooms-another-son.html|title=Mrs. Gandhi Grooms Another Son|first=Michael T.|last=Kaufman|date=13 June 1982|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n[[File:Sanjit Bunker Roy at Time 2010.jpg|thumb|left|160px|[[Bunker Roy]] (Class of 1962), social activist and the founder of [[Barefoot College]], [[Tilonia]].]]\nNotable Doon alumni to have held senior positions in Indian and Pakistani politics include the former Indian diplomat turned politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]], the former Defence Secretary of Pakistan [[Ghulam Jilani Khan]], [[Kamal Nath]], [[Rahul Gandhi]], [[Sanjay Gandhi]], [[Chief Minister of Odisha ]] [[Naveen Patnaik]], [[Jyotiraditya Madhavrao Scindia]], politican and poet [[Karan Singh]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Allana |first=Alia |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/doon-squad/464930/ |title=The Doon School Squad|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref> In the field of literature, Doon alumni include novelists [[Amitav Ghosh]], [[Vikram Seth]], [[Ardashir Vakil]], and historian [[Ramachandra Guha]];<ref>{{cite news|author=Elisabeth Bumiller |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/29/books/a-novelist-beginning-with-a-bang.html |title=A Novelist Beginning With a Bang - The New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1997-07-29 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> and in journalism, [[Prannoy Roy]], founder of [[NDTV]]; [[Aroon Purie]], founder of ''[[India Today]]'', [[Karan Thapar]], [[Virendra Prabhakar]] and [[Vikram Chandra (NDTV)|Vikram Chandra]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/microsoft-s-new-boss-is-a-window-on-a-better-school-system-9115621.html|title=Microsoft\u2019s new boss is a window on a better school system|date=7 February 2014|website=The Independent}}</ref> India's first [[Rhodes scholar]], [[Lovraj Kumar]], was an alumnus.<ref>{{cite news|author=I. M. D. Little |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-lovraj-kumar-1367199.html |title=Obituary: Lovraj Kumar|newspaper=The Independent |date=1 April 1994 |accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> [[Abhinav Bindra]], India's first Olympic gold medallist, and the mountaineer [[Nandu Jayal]] studied at the school.<ref>{{cite news|author=BBC Sports Desk |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/world_olympic_dreams/8852481.stm |title=Abhinav Bindra Indian Olympic Medallist|publisher=BBC |date=1 November 2010 |accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:Anish Kapoor at the Deutsche Guggenheim - Berlin.jpg|thumb|right|170px|[[Anish Kapoor]] (Class of 1970), artist. Designs include Chicago's [[Cloud Gate]] and [[ArcelorMittal Orbit]], [[Olympic Park, London]].]] In the field of arts and entertainment, Doon's alumni include [[Ali Fazal]], [[Roshan Seth]], [[Himani Shivpuri]], [[Chandrachur Singh]], [[Satyadeep Mishra]], and art collector [[Abhishek Poddar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christies.com/features/The-Abhishek-and-Radhika-Poddar-collection-of-Indian-Modern-and-Contemporary-Art-7960-1.aspx |title=How Abhishek and Radhika Poddar built their collection of Indian art &#124; Christie's |publisher=Christies.com |date=2016-12-18 |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> The [[Turner Prize]]-winning sculptor [[Anish Kapoor]] and [[Vivan Sundaram]] also attended Doon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/jun/07/anish-kapoor-sculpture-versailles-controversy |title=Anish Kapoor: superstar sculptor who loves to court scandal &#124; Observer profile &#124; Art and design |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref> In business, the Doon alumni include [[Analjit Singh]] of Max Group, [[Sunil Kant Munjal]], chairman of [[Hero MotoCorp]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2013/10/28/the-doon-school-grooming-ground-for-indias-wealthy-kids/|title=The Doon School: Grooming Ground For India's Wealthy Kids|first=Forbes|last=Staff|website=Forbes}}</ref> [[Rahul Akerkar]], restaurateur and founder of Indigo and Qualia; father and son [[Vikram Lal]] and [[Siddhartha Lal]] of [[Eicher Motors]]; [[A. Vellayan]], chairman of the [[Murugappa Group]], [[Ajit Narain Haksar]], the first Indian chairman of [[ITC Limited]]; [[R.C. Bhargava]], chairman of [[Maruti Suzuki]]; [[Ajay S. Shriram]], managing director of [[DCM Shriram group]], and [[Sharan Pasricha]], CEO of Ennismore hospitality developer and founder of [[The Hoxton]] and [[Gleneagles Hotel|Gleneagles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/gleneagles-is-a-sleeping-giant-well-make-it-the-best-hotel-in-the-world-lbhjf75z0|title=\u2018Gleneagles is a sleeping giant. We\u2019ll make it the best hotel in the world\u2019|first=Dominic|last=Walsh|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Faculty===\n{{See also|Category:The Doon School faculty}}\nIn the early years, many teachers came from British schools, including [[Peter Lawrence (teacher)|Peter Lawrence]] from Eton College,<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4309213.stm|title=Eton, the Raj and modern India|date=9 March 2005|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> [[Jack Gibson (schoolmaster)|Jack Gibson]] from [[Ripon Grammar School]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20041207/edit.htm|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Opinions|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref> [[John Martyn (schoolmaster)|John A. K. Martyn]] and [[R. L. Holdsworth]] from Harrow.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2002/02/24/stories/2002022400630800.htm |title=Climb every mountain |work=The Hindu |date=24 February 2002 |accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> The school's first art teacher was the artist [[Sudhir Khastgir]], from [[Visva-Bharati University|Shantiniketan]], who joined in 1936 and remained at school for twenty years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?267708 |title=Bonfire of Vanities &#124; Vishvjit P. Singh |publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> Many sculptures and murals on the campus today were created by him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jnaf.org/artist/sudhir-khastgir/|title=Sudhir Khastgir - JNAF}}</ref> The film director [[Chetan Anand (director)|Chetan Anand]] taught briefly at the school from 1940 to 1944.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/arts/dev-anand-chetan-anand-doon-school-dehradun/story/1/19703.html|title=How Doon School inspired the inimitable Dev Anand style|website=www.dailyo.in}}</ref> Mountaineer [[Gurdial Singh (mountaineer)|Gurdial Singh]] joined in 1946 as a geography teacher and led the boys on many expeditions.<ref name=\"Climb every mountain\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/50-years-later-its-happily-Everest-after/articleshow/46893756.cms|title=50 years later, it's happily Everest after &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> The cricketer and mathematics teacher, [[Sheel Vohra]], joined in 1959 and became the longest-serving master in school's history when he retired in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2014/state-editions/remembering-sheel-vohra-doon-schools-beloved-bond.html|title=Remembering Sheel Vohra, Doon School's beloved 'Bond'|first=The|last=Pioneer|website=The Pioneer}}</ref> The [[Fiji-Indian]] academic [[Satendra Nandan]] taught history at school in the early 1960s, and the [[sarod]] player [[Ashok Roy]] headed the music department from 1977 to 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fijisun.com.fj/2014/10/25/its-time-goodbye-comrades/|title=It's Time: Goodbye, COMRADES - Fiji Sun|publisher=}}</ref> [[Popular science]] author and theoretical physicist, [[Simon Singh]], taught science at Doon in 1987 before embarking on his academic and writing career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/there-s-math-in-simpsons-simon-says/story-czEcewcbqXaAuE38U6oF2K.html|title=There's math in Simpsons, Simon says|date=11 January 2014|work=[[Hindustan Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Schools|Education}}\n* [[The Doon School Old Boys' Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://archive.is/20121219012747/http://fullcirclebooks.in/content/chhota-hazri-days-doscos-yatra ''Chhota Hazri Days: A Dosco's Yatra''] by Sanjiv Bathla, [[Rupa & Co.]], 2010 {{ISBN|978-81-291-1694-9}}.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130323003553/http://www.penguinbooksindia.com/en/content/sahibs-who-loved-india ''Sahibs who Loved India''] by [[Khushwant Singh]], [[Penguin Books]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-0-14-341580-0}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=oFRF6vs5algC&q=Doon+School&dq=the+doon+school+sixty+years+on+pushpinder&source=gbs_word_cloud_r&cad=5#v=snippet&q=Doon%20School&f=false ''The Corporeal Image''] by David McDougall, [[Princeton University Press]], 2006, {{ISBN|978-0-691-12156-7}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=IRBFAAAAYAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Trees of Chandbagh''] by K.C. Sinha, Konark Publishers, 1996, {{ISBN|978-81-220-0457-1}}.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=3sVlHQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''For Hills To Climb''] by Gurdial Singh and Nalni Dhar, The Doon School Old Boys' Society, 2001.\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=NEdmQgAACAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Doon, The Story of a School''], IPSS (1985) edited by Sumer Singh, published by the Indian Public Schools Society 1985. ASIN B0006ENF66\n* [http://dsobs.net/currentrb/current_rosebowl.php ''The Rose Bowl''],  a periodic newsletter by the Doon School Old Boys' Society\n* [https://books.google.com/books?q=Constructing+PostColonial+India:+National+Character+and+the+Doon+School, ''Constructing Post-Colonial India: National Character and the Doon School''] by Sanjay Srivastva, published by [[Routledge]] 1998 {{ISBN|0-203-98027-1}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |b=no |n=no |q=The Doon School |s=Category:The Doon School |v=no |species=no |commons=Category:The Doon School }}\n* {{Official website|1=http://www.doonschool.com/|name = Official website}}\n* [http://www.dsobs.net/ Website of the Doon School Old Boys' Society]\n* [http://store.doonschool.com/ The Doon School - Gift Store]\n\n{{The Doon School}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doon School}}\n[[Category:The Doon School| ]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Round Square schools]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in India]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in India]]\n[[Category:Cambridge schools in India]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:Schools in Dehradun]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1935]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "CallMeByYourMane", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMountaineering:during", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Doon_School"}
{"title_page": "Banj\u014d Ginga", "text_new": "{{Expand Japanese|\u9280\u6cb3\u4e07\u4e08|topic=actor|date=June 2015}}\n{{More footnotes|BLP=yes|date=February 2014}}\n{{Japanese name|Ginga}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Banj\u014d Ginga\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \u9280\u6cb3 \u4e07\u4e08\n| native_name_lang   = ja\n| birth_name         = Takashi Tanaka\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1948|11|12}}\n| birth_place        = [[Kofu, Yamanashi]], Japan\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} Death date then birth -->\n| death_place        = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = {{flatlist| \n*[[Actor]]\n*[[Voice acting in Japan|voice actor]]\n*[[Narrative|narrator]]\n}}\n| years_active       = 1970\u2013present\n| agent              = [[Aoni Production]]\n| height             = 173 cm\n| spouse             = [[Gara Takashima]]\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Banj\u014d Ginga'''|\u9280\u6cb3 \u4e07\u4e08|Ginga Banj\u014d|born November 12, 1948}}, sometimes credited as his real name {{nihongo|'''Takashi Tanaka'''|\u7530\u4e2d \u5d07|Tanaka Takashi}}, is a Japanese actor, [[Voice acting in Japan|voice actor]] and narrator who was born in [[Kofu, Yamanashi]]. Ginga is affiliated with [[Aoni Production]]. He is married to voice actress [[Gara Takashima]].\n\nKnown for his deep baritone voice, his most well-known roles includes [[Gihren Zabi]] (''[[Mobile Suit Gundam]]''), Crocodine (''[[Dragon Quest: Dai no Daib\u014dken]]''), Jean Paul Rocchina (''[[Armored Trooper Votoms]]''), Sh\u014dhei Harada (''[[Touch (manga)|Touch]]''), [[List of Fist of the North Star characters#Souther|Souther]] (''[[Fist of the North Star]]'', original 1980s series), [[List of M\u00c4R characters|Babbo]] (''[[M\u00c4R]]''), [[Heihachi Mishima]] and the various models of [[Jack (Tekken)|Jack]] in the ''[[Tekken]]'' series, and [[Liquid Snake]] and [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Zero|Zero]] in the ''[[Metal Gear (series)|Metal Gear]]'' series.\n\nHis hobbies include painting, salsa dance, riding horses and playing music.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television animation===\n;1977\n*''[[Planet Robot Danguard Ace]]'' \u2013 Doppler\n\n;1978\n*''[[Daikengo]]'' \u2013 Doctor Gudda, Emperor Mazeran\n*''[[Galaxy Express 999]]'' \u2013 Doctor Ban, Clone C (ep 36)\n*''[[The Perrine Story]]'' \u2013 Theodor\n*''[[Muteki K\u014djin Daitarn 3]]'' \u2013 Neros\n\n;1979\n*''[[Entaku no Kishi Monogatari: Moero Arthur]]'' \u2013 Labick\n*''[[Mobile Suit Gundam]]'' \u2013 Gihren Zabi, Cozun Graham\n*''[[Koguma no Misha]]'' \u2013 Misha's Father\n*''[[Cyborg 009]]'' \u2013 Geronimo Junior/005, Vishnu\n\n;1980\n*''[[Space Warrior Baldios]]'' \u2013 Alan, King Bado\n*''[[Astro Boy (1980 TV series)|Astro Boy]]'' \u2013 Gallon\n*''[[Densetsu Kyojin Ideon]]'' \u2013 Damido Pecchi\n*''[[Mahou Shoujo Lalabel]]'' \u2013 Viscous\n*''[[Moero Arthur: Hakuba no Oji]]'' \u2013 Labick\n\n;1981\n*''[[Swiss Family Robinson]]'' \u2013 Edward\n*''[[Galaxy Cyclone Braiger]]'' \u2013 Rasputin\n*''[[Tiger Mask II]]'' \u2013 Antonio Inoki\n*''[[Taiyou no Kiba Dougram]]'' \u2013 Chico\n*''[[Dr. Slump]]'' \u2013 Mr. Kimidori\n*''[[Hello! Sandybell]]'' \u2013 Edward\n\n;1982\n*''[[Ai no Senshi Rainbowman]]'' \u2013 Heinz Shousa\n*''[[Ochamegami Monogatari Korokoro Poron]]'' \u2013 Poseidan\n*''[[Armored Fleet Dairugger XV]]'' \u2013 Caponero, Mack Chukker\n*''[[Galactic Gale Baxinger]]'' \u2013 Geruba Zorba\n*''[[The Kabocha Wine]]'' \u2013 Dekkin\n*''[[Space Adventure Cobra]]'' \u2013 Col. Velga\n*''[[Sent\u014d Mecha Xabungle]]'' \u2013 Fatman Big, Narrator, Timp\n*''[[Fuku-chan]]'' \u2013 Mr. Arakuma\n\n;1983\n*''[[Genesis Climber Mospeada]]'' \u2013 Jonathan Wolf\n*''[[Armored Trooper Votoms]]'' \u